<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, December 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodia's King Norodom Sihanouk returned to his
homeland today after undergoing medical treatment in China for one
month.
</P>
<P>
Arriving on a special Royal Air Cambodge flight, Sihanouk was
greeted by Hun Sen and senior members of his government.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted to be back," Sihanouk said on his arrival. He
also said that he is planning to meet people of all circles in
Cambodia, including politicians who have recently returned from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- The U.N. arms inspection in Iraq entered its 12th
consecutive day today since the weapons experts were allowed to
return and resume work in Baghdad late last month. No incidents
were reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Iraqi News Agency, 11 inspection
teams of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on dismantling
Iraq's weapons of mass destruction, today set out for declared and
sudden visits to Iraqi industrial, trade and scientific sites.
</P>
<P>
Hussan Mohammed Ameen, director general of Iraqi National
Monitoring Department, the Iraqi counterpart of UNSCOM, said the
Iraqis have been very cooperative, with no delays or problems
reported.
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Visiting Russian President Boris Yeltsin announced
here today that Russia will unilaterally cut its ground and naval
forces in the northwest region by more than 40 percent beginning
in 1999.
</P>
<P>
"From January 1, 1999, Russia will unilaterally reduce its land
and naval units, especially in northwestern Russia, by more than
40 percent," Yeltsin, who arrived here Tuesday for a state visit,
said in a speech to the Swedish parliament.
</P>
<P>
In the speech, Yeltsin proposed a series of confidence-building
measures in the border zones and along the seacoast of the Baltic
region designed to guarantee peace and stability in northern
Europe.
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea and the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
today agreed finally on the terms of the IMF bailout loan to South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Deputy Prime Minister Lim Chang-yuel and visiting
International Monetary Fund (IMF) Managing Director Michel
Camdessus arrived at a complete agreement, South Korea's Yonhap
news agency reported. Camdessus flied into Seoul today.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the South Korean government, Lim signed a letter
of intent and handed it to Camdessus.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement coming after a difficult 10-day
negotiations beginning November 24, the IMF and the United States
and Japan will give an assistance of about 57 billion U.S. dollars
for bailing out the South Korean economy from its current
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The first tranche of 10 billion U.S. dollars will arrive in the
country within the week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
