<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Adopts Guidelines for 1998 Employment Policies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The young and adult alike will
be offered fresh starts to land jobs next year as the European
Union is striving to improve employment in its member states.
</P>
<P>
The striving effort was adopted today by the European
Commission following the conclusion of the European Council on
employment held on November 20 and 21.
</P>
<P>
Every unemployed young person will be offered a new start, in
the form of training, retraining, work practice or job, before
reaching six months of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
Unemployed adults are also offered fresh starts before reaching
12 months of unemployment, according to the final proposal adopted
for guidelines for member states' employment policies for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The proposal highlighted the EU's employment strategy of
employability, entrepreneurship, adaptability and equal
opportunities for men and women.
</P>
<P>
Active measures will be required of member states to improve
the employability of the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
A fixed target will be set for increasing the number of the
unemployed who are offered training or retraining to gradually
achieve the average of the three most employed member states, or
20 percent at least.
</P>
<P>
Social partners in member states are also urged by the proposal
to conclude as soon as possible agreements with a view to
increasing the possibilities for training, work experience and
traineeship to promote employability.
</P>
<P>
Actions of the member states alone will not suffice, said the
commission, the executive agency of the 15-nation union which now
has an average unemployment rate at 10.7 percent as of October.
</P>
<P>
The commission also appealed to school systems in member states
to improve their curricula in order to reduce substantially the
number of young people who drop out of schools early on.
</P>
<P>
The commission proposal urged schools to equip young people
with greater ability to adapt to technological and economic
changes and with skills relevant to the labor market by means of
implementing or developing apprenticeship training where
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
The final proposal will be adopted by the social affairs
council meeting of the EU slated for December 15. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
