<HEADLINE> Mubarak Heads for Reconciling with Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- President Hosni Mubarak today
embarked on a voyage aimed to clean grudges with the Gulf light
weight Qatar through the mediation of Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak left here on a previously unannounced visit to Riyadh,
accompanied by ministers of information and foreign affairs,
presidential cabinet chief and political advisor.
</P>
<P>
The visit came one day after Mubarak received a message from
Saudi King Fahd on a fence-mending between Egypt and Qatar and sent
his foreign minister Amr Moussa to Riyadh on a lightning visit to
get acquainted with the details.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has been on good terms with both Egypt and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Khalifa Al-Thani today
regretted growing strains with Egypt and announced he is leaving
for Saudi Arabia today to remove misunderstanding, the Qatari News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In a pre-departure statement at Doha Airport, the emir told
reporters that he will meet with his "brothers" King Fahd and
Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
He said he could not miss this chance to express his
appreciation of King Fahd's initiative and sincere efforts exerted
by Saudi Crown Prince, Deputy Premier and Head of the National
Guard Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-Qatari ties deteriorated in October as Egypt was ready
to boycott the fourth Middle East and North Africa Economic
Conference, of which Qatar was the host. Cairo cited lack of
progress in the Middle East peace process as the reason for its
absence at the Arab-Israeli conference in Doha.
</P>
<P>
Qatar responded with a ban on the entry of nationals of Egypt
and other nine countries as a security precaution for the Doha
meeting, infuriating Cairo and other Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
On November 12, a senior Qatari official accused Cairo of being
the "maestro" in an abortive 1996 coup to oust the Gulf sheikdom's
emir, who himself toppled his father in a bloodless palace coup in
1995.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has denied the charges and repeatedly implied that Cairo
was above trading insults with Doha.
</P>
<P>
As the crack deepened, Egyptian foreign minister Moussa last
week asked Qatari ambassador to Cairo for an explanation of the
coup accusation and recalled his ambassador to Doha for the second
time in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Moussa had said relations with Qatar would be kept even at the
least possible levels so as not to worsen the already tense
inter-Arab relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
