<HEADLINE> Blair Positive N.Ireland Peace to Be Settled by May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said he believed a Northern Ireland peace deal could be
reached by next May.
</P>
<P>
"We have the May deadline and I think that we can make it,"
Blair said in an interview with Irish television today.
</P>
<P>
"I think there is a recognition on the part of them that
progress is there to be made soon rather than later. Obviously we
will do everything we can to move it on," he said.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland set next May as the target for the parties
to produce proposals that the government will put to referendums
in Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
The multi-party peace talks on the fate of Britain's divided
province started in September after the Irish Republican Army
(IRA) called a cease-fire in July. The truce enabled the IRA's
political wing Sinn Fein to join other parties in Northern Ireland
to the peace talks together with the two governments for the first
time to try to find an end to decades of conflict.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, three high-security long-term IRA prisoners were
transferred from British jail to a prison in the Irish Republic
today, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
Their transfer followed top-level contact between London and
Dublin. It is seen as a key confidence-building move aimed at
advancing the slow-going peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
