<HEADLINE> US Congressman for Talks in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi today held talks with visiting U.S. congressman Tom
Campbell on regional and bilateral issues.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman from the Foreign Ministry was quoted by the
Ethiopian News Agency as saying that Premier Meles briefed the
congressman on efforts underway on the part of the different
Somali factions to bring about national reconciliation in the
country.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said, the two sides have also discussed the
initiative of the Inter-Governmental Authority on Development
(IGAD) in helping the conflicting parties in Sudan, who are
engaged in a war that has so far cost the lives of more than a
million people, to reach a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
Meles also briefed Campbell about Ethiopia's difference with
the International Monetary Fund, and told him that the government
of Ethiopia will go ahead with its reform measures in spite of
the differences, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to the spokesman, Ethiopian Foreign
Minister Seyoum Mesfin today also held talks with the visiting
U.S. congressman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said, Seyoum had discussed with the congressman
about the situation in Somalia, Sudan and countries of the Great
Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, he said, also discussed issues regarding to the
use of the Nile water.
</P>
<P>
Seyoum told Campbell that all the countries of the Nile river
should be able to tackle the problem standing in the way of
communal usage of the river.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia's desire to obtain her share of the waters of the
Nile is ever more pressing, due to the nation's increasing water
need for irrigation, hydropower generation and other purposes,
Seyoum said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. congressman arrived here yesterday for a four-day
working visit to Ethiopia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
