<HEADLINE> Europeans More Eurosceptic Than 2 Years Ago: Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Four Europeans in 10 now
believe their countries benefit from European Union membership
whereas 36 percent, or almost as many, believe otherwise.
</P>
<P>
The latest Eurobarometer poll conducted by the European
Commission, published today in the European Report journal, found
that European citizens have become more sceptical than two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The trend of having come to doubt the benefits of EU membership
in the last two years has been particularly strong in Italy and
Belgium while support for the union has increased in Denmark,
Luxembourg, Britain and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Forty-six percent of the Europeans polled regard membership as
a "good thing," 15 percent as a "bad thing," and 30 percent have
no opinion either way.
</P>
<P>
A majority of citizens, 51 percent, claim to be Europeans up to
a point while the proportion of those faithful to their national
status remains constant at 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
Support for the single currency has also fallen over the past
two years, down by 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Forty-seven percent of the Europeans support the introduction
of the single currency in 1999 whereas 40 percent are against it
and 13 percent do not know for sure.
</P>
<P>
Questioned over EU enlargement, the Europeans greatly supported
the accession of Switzerland (72 percent) and Norway (69 percent).
</P>
<P>
These were followed by Iceland (56 percent), Malta (49
percent), Poland (46 percent), the Czech Republic (43 percent) and
Cyprus (40 percent). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
