<HEADLINE> Further German Rate Hike Unlikely This Year: Experts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the German
central bank predicted today that Germany is unlikely to take
another move to raise its key interest rates in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Ernst Welteke, a board member of the Bundesbank, told the
German investment magazine Boerse Online that a rate hike was not
an issue for the moment because there was no major inflationary
danger in Germany and Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, he also cautioned that the situation might change if
the U.S. dollar climbed sharply against the German mark in the
coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
Michael Heise, chief economist with the German DG Bank, today
said that he did not expect any German rate increases before
February or March next year.
</P>
<P>
The modest domestic economic growth and the slow price
increases did not justify a rate hike in Germany, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that a dollar exchange rate, which currently
fluctuated between 1.70 and 1.80 German marks and could even
increase to 1.85 marks next year, would not arouse major
inflationary risks in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Germany's two key interest rates, the discount rate and the
Lombard rate, have been kept unchanged at 2.5 percent and 4.5
percent since April 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the other benchmark rate, the securities repurchase
rate, was raised sharply from 3.0 percent to 3.3 percent in early
October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
