<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Close Down Factories Without Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe government today
warned to close companies without adequate health and safety
measures in order to reduce occupational deaths and injuries.
</P>
<P>
Opening a seminar on health and safety at work places
organized by the National Social Security Authority (NSSA) here,
Public Service, Labor and Social Welfare Minister Florance
Chitauro said stringent measures to ensure improvement in safety
at work places will continue to be implemented.
</P>
<P>
"The NSSA will continue to be more aggressive and even close
down more companies or work places which are sub-standard in the
year 1998," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The government's decision to close down the affected factories
came after a research which shows that 80 percent of work places
lack adequate health and safety measures.
</P>
<P>
The lack of proper management of health and safety issues in
the work environment resulted in disabling injuries and deaths on
workers averaging over 20,000 annually for the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Chitauro said the NSSA would next year implement a program
called "results oriented program" in which health and safety
officers would be placed at work places with high rate accidents
to monitor implementation of safety programs.
</P>
<P>
This year the NSSA issued about 55 prohibition notices to
companies and work places with sub-standard work conditions that
have injured or killed employees.
</P>
<P>
The prohibition notices said that the companies and work
places would be forced to close if they do not improve the safety
conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
