<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Astronauts Aboard Columbia Begin Second Spacewalk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Two astronauts aboard the
space shuttle Columbia today floated out the hatch of shuttle and
successfully conducted five hours of test for space station
equipment during their spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
American Winston Scott and Japanese Takao Doi floated out of
Columbia's airlock into the shuttle's cargo bay at 4:20 a.m. (0920
GMT) to begin their second spacewalk of the mission. They set up a
small hand-operated crane that NASA designed to help spacewalking
astronauts assemble the new international space station. Scott
then used the crane to move a box.
</P>
<P>
In the outing hours, Scott also held up the robotic camera and
then let go, watching as the camera slowly propelled itself with
little jet thrusters. The roving eye flitted high above the
shuttle's open cargo bay, sending live views of Columbia and the
astronauts down to Earth.
</P>
<P>
The crewmen couldn't conduct the test during last week's
spacewalk because they had to chase a runaway science satellite.
</P>
<P>
The satellite rescue took up almost half of the seven and a
half hours during their November 24 spacewalk. Scott and Doi did
not have time to use the crane to lift a 50-pound object or to
release the prototype camera.
</P>
<P>
The second spacewalk was urgently arranged by NASA before the
satellite was back on board the shuttle for Friday's trip home
because space station construction is to start within half a year
and there was no arrangement for more spacewalks before the first
assembly flight next June.
</P>
<P>
A crane similar to the one tested will be used all the time to
move objects outside the space station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
