<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toyota to Set Up Auto Assembly Plant in Northern France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese auto-maker Toyota
will set up a new assembly plant in Valenciennes in northern
France, which will create about 1,000 jobs in the first phase of
development by 2001, said government officials today.
</P>
<P>
French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin and Toyota President
Hiroshi Okuda will officially announce the plan next Tuesday, said
reports.
</P>
<P>
Toyota will invest 3.5 billion francs (600 million US dollars)
in the first phase by 2001, and 1.5 billion francs (250 million
dollars) in the second phase by 2005, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The plant will be capable of producing 100,000 automobiles each
year from 2001, and will double its capacity of production by
2005.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Industry, Finance and Economy Dominique
Strauss-Kahn confirmed today that Toyota will set up an auto
assembly plant in France without providing further details.
</P>
<P>
The installation of a plant in France will allow Toyota to
pierce through the French market, where it sold only 17,562
vehicles in 1996, or 0.8 percent of the total sold in the country,
said Agence France-Presse (AFP).
</P>
<P>
The location of Valenciennes will also allow Toyota to expand
its market in nearby Germany and get back-up from its plant in
Britain through the Channel Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
The strong presence of automobile industry in northern France,
its proximity to Belgium and the Netherlands, the good quality of
the local labor force as well as France's decision to enter the
European monetary union in the first wave are also elements which
encouraged Toyota to choose Valenciennes to establish the plant,
said AFP.
</P>
<P>
Among the competitors of Valenciennes were Longway in the
Lorraine region of France, Ireland and Poland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
