<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Denies Queen's Role in Gandhi's Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Surya
Bahadur Thapa and Foreign Minister Kamal Thapa today strongly
condemned an Indian magazine report which alleged that Nepali
Queen Aishwarya was involved in the assassination of Indian former
prime minister Rajiv Gandhi, the official RSS news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The December 8 issue of India Today published earlier claimed
that the Nepali Queen "had asked Major General Aditya Shamsher
Jang Bahadur, an honorary aide-de-camp to King Birendra, to
arrange for the assassination of Gandhi."
</P>
<P>
A press communique issued by the Prime Minister Office said
that the news report has been published with an ill-intention of
damaging the age-old cordial relations between Nepal and India.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Kamal Thapa handed over a note verbale to
Indian Ambassador K.V. Rajan, expressing condemnation for "such a
malicious and irresponsible act of outright misinformation."
</P>
<P>
Indian Ambassador Rajan said in a statement that "this report
is based on completely unverified and unsubstantiated information
from which the government of India disassociates itself."
</P>
</TEXT>
