<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Ruling MPs Support Netanyahu Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Eighteen members of the
Knesset (Parliament) of Israel's ruling parties have issued a
statement in support of the cabinet plan of conditional troop
withdrawal from the West Bank, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The statement, initiated by Roman Bronfman of the Yisrael
Ba'aliya (Israel Immigration) party, also called for advancing the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The statement were signed by Knesset members of the Yisrael
Ba'aliya party, the Third Way party, the Gesher (Bridge) party and
other coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet Sunday approved Netanyahu's proposal to pull
out troops from West Bank under the condition that the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) steps up fight against terrorism. But the
plan set no date and extent of the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties, however, lashed out at the plan, calling it
as a hindrance to peace. Labor Party whip Raanan Cohen described
Netanyahu's plan as "the continued burial of the peace process."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Labor will submit a no-confidence motion
against the Netanyahu government.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing Meretz leader Yossi Sarid charged that Netanyahu
only pretended to push forward the peace process and said the
government decision has nothing new.
</P>
<P>
But Likud spokeswoman Ronit Eckstein rejected the charges of
the oppositions, saying "it is difficult for the Labor to accept
the fact that while the left-wing parties sing and dream about
peace, it is only the Likud government which furthers a stable and
safe peace agreement."
</P>
<P>
The Third Way party whip Yehuda Harel called on the Labor "to
ignore narrow political interests" and to support Netanyahu in
carrying out the pullback plan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel's four-member ministerial committee,
authorized to draw up a map and timetable for the withdrawal,
convened this morning. It was expected to reach a conclusion as
early as Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
