<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Resents Russian Arms Export to Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu today sent a harsh message to Russian President
Boris Yeltsin over Russia's supply of missile technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
The message was given by Netanyahu to visiting Russian Deputy
Foreign Minister Victor Possavalyuk when they held talks here in
the Prime Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Office said Netanyahu delivered the
"sharp message" to Yeltsin "despite good relations between Israel
and Russia and the desire to advance those relations."
</P>
<P>
In the message, the statement said, Netanyahu hinted that
bilateral relations could be harmed by Moscow's continued supply
of ballistic technology to Iran.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told Possavalyuk that Israel viewed with great
severity the supply of such technology to Iran, because it is "a
matter of survival for Israel." "The arming of Iran automatically
endangers not only Israel, but other countries as well, including
Russia itself," Netanyahu said.
</P>
<P>
Possavalyuk said he would pass the message on to Yeltsin,
adding that in any case he hoped the relations between the two
countries would remain good and not be harmed.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Netanyahu reviewed the diplomatic process
in the region and Israeli Cabinet's Sunday decision on
conditionally carrying out the second-phase Israeli troop
redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Possavalyuk said Russia put emphasis on the redeployments. He
added that in order to improve bilateral relations, Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin would visit Israel in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
Possavalyuk, who was appointed by Yeltsin as the Middle East
peace envoy, arrived here for a visit to explore ways of pushing
forward Israeli-Palestinian peace process and reviving
Israeli-Syrian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
He already met with Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy
Tuesday, voicing Russia's readiness to help renew the multilateral
talks which he said are a key component of the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The Russian envoy even offered Moscow as a venue for such
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
