<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Court Orders Striking Workers Back to Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 3 (Xinhua) -- After several hours'
deliberations, Israeli National Labor Court judges today ordered
the striking Trade Union workers to return to their jobs by 6
p.m. this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide strike was launched by Israeli Trade Union this
morning in protest of government plans for wages reform and
privatization.
</P>
<P>
Upon receiving the court order, the Trade Union leaders have
been meeting to consider their next steps and how to respond to
the court decision.
</P>
<P>
Trade Union Chairman Amir Peretz is due to meet with Finance
Minister Ya'akov Neeman at the Presidential residence in Jerusalem
this evening in an effort to work out the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Israeli President Ezer Weizman has called for a resolution for
the controversy between the Treasury and Trade Union in order to
"prevent the collapse of the economy and services".
</P>
<P>
Some 700,000 workers reportedly took part in today's stoppage,
which paralyzed many sectors of national economy.
</P>
<P>
Most government offices and companies were shut down while
hospitals, telecommunications, banks, post offices and other
services were affected.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Manufacture Association estimated the damage from
today's strike at 53 million shekels (about 15 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The industrial action was triggered by Neeman's remarks on
Monday, in which he called striking workers "exploding bombs" and
"enemies from within." Peretz declared the strike Tuesday at an
emergency gathering of thousands of union members in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
The strike was the latest in a Trade Union battle against
government economic reform plans, which have sparked fears that
worker's rights would be prejudiced.
</P>
<P>
Early this week, 150,000 clerks and municipal workers staged a
two-day strike against cost-cutting measures taken by local
authorities. They resumed work only after the National Labor
Court issued a back-to-work order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
