<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France: NATO Military Structure Reform Incomplete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- France said today that the reform
of the NATO integrated military structure remains "incomplete" and
thus does not allow France to re-integrate into it.
</P>
<P>
"The reform of the military structure of NATO remains
incomplete in what concerns the development within the heart of
the alliance of the European identity of security and defense and
in what concerns the need of a better sharing of responsibilities
between Europeans and Americans," said French Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret.
</P>
<P>
She said that because of this, France considers it not prime
time for it to return to the structure now.
</P>
<P>
But she praised the agreement reached in Brussels Tuesday by
NATO countries on the reform of the military structure as "an
important step in the process of adaptation of NATO" and toward "a
greater flexibility and a rationalization of the military
structure of the alliance."
</P>
<P>
France abstained from Tuesday's voting at the half-yearly
defense ministers' session in the NATO headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"The reform should continue and France remains ready for
dialogue," said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
The Western military alliance reached an agreement upon its new
command structure after two major disputes were solved via mutual
agreements between Greece and Turkey, Britain and Spain.
</P>
<P>
NATO plans to reduce its regional headquarters from 65 to 20
and make regional headquarters more international with up to 50
percent of officers from countries other than the host country.
</P>
<P>
Spain will be able to return by 1999 to the NATO integrated
military structure from which it withdrew in 1986, along with the
entry into the structure by three new members of NATO: Poland, the
Czech Republic and Hungary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
