<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US New Home Sales Take Slim Drop in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. new home sales
declined in October, for the second time in three months, but
still remained at a relative high level, the Commerce Department
said here today.
</P>
<P>
New single-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted annual
rate of 797,000, 1.7 percent lower from September.
</P>
<P>
However, nationwide sales for this year's first 10 months were
running 6 percent ahead of the same period last year. Besides,
October also marked the 22nd month of sales higher than 700,000,
the longest such stretch since the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that the robust job market and low mortgage
rates are forces behind the development trend. Nevertheless,
they're expecting sales to level off next year.
</P>
<P>
The inventory of unsold new homes totaled 290,000 in October.
That's a 4.4 month supply at the current sales rate. It was the
10th consecutive month that the ratio has been below five months,
the most since the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
By region, sales of new homes fell 1.6 percent in the Northeast
to 63,000, the lowest level since May 1996, and 1.5 percent in the
Midwest to 128,000, the lowest since March. They plunged 5.7
percent in the West to 230,000. In the South, sales rose 1.3
percent to 377,000, the best since February.
</P>
<P>
The nationwide median price of a new home was 141,500 U.S.
dollars in October, down 1.6 percent from a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
