<HEADLINE> Russian, Yugoslav Premiers Meet in Moscow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian Premier Viktor
Chernomyrdin and his visiting Yugoslav counterpart, Radoje Kontic,
today held two-hour talks and signed a package of documents on
further development of bilateral cooperation, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two sides signed an agreement on granting a state credit by
Russia to Yugoslavia to finance deliveries of Russian equipment,
goods and services.
</P>
<P>
They also concluded a memorandum to liberalize trade between
Russia and Yugoslavia, an agreement on military and technical
cooperation as well as a program of cooperation in culture,
education and science for 1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting Chernomyrdin told reporters that Russia will
do its utmost for the earliest return of Yugoslavia to the United
Nations as well as other international political, economic and
financial organizations.
</P>
<P>
Kontic, for his part, praised Russia's positive role in
settling the crisis on the Balkans. He underlined that, apart from
problems of the peace process in the region, special attention at
the talks was given to improvement of Russian-Yugoslav trade and
economic relations and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He noted, "The reached understandings give guarantees for
normalizing our relations."
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav premier arrived in Moscow Tuesday evening for a
two-day official visit, the first one by Yugoslavia's head of
government to Russia since the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia was
formed in 1992. 
</P>
