<HEADLINE> UK Launches Pre-Christmas Anti-Drink-Drive Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government has
launched a pre-Christmas anti-drink-drive campaign which urges
motorists to have no alcohol at all before driving, said local
press reports today.
</P>
<P>
The central message of the 2 million pound (3.4 million US
dollar) campaign is to "Have none for the road" and that any
drinking increases the risk of having an accident that can cause
death or serious injury.
</P>
<P>
The three-week television and radio advertising blitz for the
first time targets young women as one of the groups most likely to
offend in addition to the traditional target groups of 17 to
24-year-old males and middle-aged men.
</P>
<P>
The campaign came in advance of government proposals to reduce
the permitted alcohol limit.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that government officials will consult in the
new year on a scheme to decrease the limit from 80 milligrams of
alcohol per 100 milliliters of blood to 50 milligrams.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Transport Minister Gavin Strang said that he wanted
to cut the annual deaths in drink-related accidents, which have
remained static at about 540 for each of the last four years.
</P>
</TEXT>
