<HEADLINE> Iraq Returns Removed Equipment to Original Places </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq announced today that all
the removed under-monitoring equipments had been fully returned to
their original places, a sign of Baghdad's cooperation with
U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency INA quoted a senior official as saying
that the Iraqi leadership issued directives to this effect so that
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on eliminating Iraqi weapons of
mass destruction can easily resume its work in the country.
</P>
<P>
The equipment was evacuated to other places as a precautionary
measure to ensure their safety against potential U.S. military
attack, the Iraqis had claimed.
</P>
<P>
Hussan Mohammed Ameen, director general of Iraqi National
Monitoring Department, the Iraqi counterpart of UNSCOM, said the
U.N. arms inspectors, who resumed their work on November 22,
visited all the sites from which the equipment was removed.
</P>
<P>
They had ascertained that the equipment returned had absolutely
not been used over the period from October 30 to November 22 when
inspection was suspended, said Ameen.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official demanded that UNSCOM objectively present
the U.N. Security Council and world public opinion with the
results it had concluded in this respect.
</P>
<P>
U.N. arms inspection entered its 12th day in a row since the
arms experts returned to Baghdad on October 21. The Iraqi have
been cooperative with no incidents being reported during the
inspection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
