<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Halts New Gas-Fired Power Stations to Save Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said today he would do everything he could to assist the
coal industry.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in parliament, the prime minister, "We want to
preserve as much of the deep-mined coal industry as we possibly
can."
</P>
<P>
Miners, who have seen their numbers plummet in the past decade
from nearly 250,000 to 20,000, have called for help to prevent the
closure of more coal mines because of a fall in sales to power
generators.
</P>
<P>
To aid the coal mine sector, Blair announced a moratorium on
power station approvals, saying that the National Grid Group Plc
had been advising the government for some time of the dangers of
relying too much on gas-powered fuel stations.
</P>
<P>
The coal industry itself has predicted up to 5,000 jobs may go
and eight pits could close as the country's biggest mining firm --
RJB Mining Plc -- has a hard time securing new supply contracts.
</P>
<P>
"We are working as intensively as we can to try and ensure that
the generators and RJB come together," Blair said.
</P>
<P>
"We obviously want to preserve as much of the deep mined coal
industry as we possibly can," he added.
</P>
<P>
There were 170 coal mines in 1984 but the number has been
reduced to a mere 23. At the same time, nearly 250,000 people
worked in the coal mines in the early 1980s, but their numbers
have dwindled rapidly as cheaper and cleaner gas replaced coal as
the electricity generators' favorite fuel.
</P>
<P>
The advance of gas is now gathering pace as long-term coal
supply contracts between RJB and the generators expire on March
31. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
