<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Open to Take Part in Compensation Fund of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- France today said it remains
open to participate in the international fund to compensate the
families of the victims of Nazi robbery during World War II, but
said it has not taken any decision on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the fund was announced Tuesday in London
by the United States and Britain at the international conference
on Nazi gold.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Anne Gazeau-Secret said
that France will not make any official announcement during the
four-day conference in London, which the French authorities
described as "purely historical" rather than political in nature.
</P>
<P>
France is expected to recover 2.2 tons out of 5.5 tons of the
remainder of Nazi gold seized by the Allies from Germany after the
war.
</P>
<P>
Local media reports quoted French representatives at the London
conference as saying Tuesday that France will compensate the Jews
robbed by Nazis on its soil by itself, instead of through the
international fund.
</P>
<P>
"The position of France on the international fund remains open.
A partial participation is possible," said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
She stressed that each state having the right to retrieving its
part of Nazi gold should also have the right to decide which way
to re-distribute them to the victims of Nazi robbery.
</P>
<P>
"The idea of an international fund inscribes itself in this
context, in order to give the states having the right the
possibility of choosing between a contribution to this fund or
following a step of the same nature in the national framework,"
she said.
</P>
<P>
She said that how France will re-distribute the remainder of
Nazi gold to be returned will be decided by the Matteoli
Commission, which was set up in February by the government to
investigate the situation of robbery of Jews by Nazis in France
during the occupation period.
</P>
<P>
"This commission will publish a report in the coming days,"
said the spokeswoman, adding that the French government is keeping
"close concertation" with Jewish and other representative
organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0031 </DOCNO>
