<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Leaves Mexico for Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang
Zemin left here for home this morning at the conclusion of his
four-day state visit to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Upon departure, he cabled his thanks to his Mexican
counterpart, E. Zedillo, for the warm reception accorded to him
during his stay in the Latin American country. It was the first
visit to Mexico by a Chinese head of state in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
President Zedillo unexpectedly came to the airport to see Jiang
off and the two leaders hugged each other before Jiang climbed the
plane.
</P>
<P>
Jiang and Zedillo held talks Monday on bilateral relations and
major international issues. They agreed to establish partnership
of overall cooperation between the two countries for the next
century.
</P>
<P>
Zedillo, speaking at a dinner in honor of President Jiang
Monday evening, stressed that his government attaches importance
to developing cooperative ties with China, as the two countries
hold identical or similar views on many international issues.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang, on his part, reiterated China's willingness to
better relations with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
China and Mexico established diplomatic relations in 1972 and
trade between the two countries reached 539 million U.S. dollars
in 1996 and is expected to grow to 700 million dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents were present Monday at a signing ceremony at
which several agreements on cooperation in such fields as
consulate affairs, sports, social science and agriculture were
inked. These agreements will surely give a new push to the
ever-growing bilateral ties, they believed.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders have met for five times so far. They both
called the visit by Jiang to Mexico a success.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang came over here from a four-day state visit to
Canada, where he met with Canadian leaders and business
representatives.
</P>
<P>
He also attended the fifth informal Asia Pacific Economic
Cooperation (APEC) leaders' meeting held in the Canadian west
coastal city of Vancouver on November 24-25. At the meeting Jiang
stressed, among other things, the need for promoting economic and
technological cooperation among the APEC members, while continuing
to pursuit trade and investment liberalization.
</P>
<P>
Among his entourage were Vice Premier and Foreign Minister Qian
Qichen and Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu
Yi. This has pointed to China's readiness to develop both
political and economic relations with foreign countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
