<HEADLINE> Russia Starts Ballistic Missiles Reduction in Barents Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Russia started elimination of
its ballistic missiles carried by submarines in the Barents Sea
today, according to the Itar-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
The first RSM-52 missile was launched at 9:00 Moscow time (0600
GMT) from a nuclear submarine in the Barents Sea. At a height of
about 3.5 kilometers and 100 kilometers from the shore it
destroyed itself.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the operation was being watched by seven
military experts from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The action was taken under the Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty
(START-1). A total of 20 missiles will be disposed of on December
3-4. Another 11 missiles were planned to be destroyed today.
</P>
<P>
The START-1 treaty signed in December 1994 allows no more than
6,000 nuclear warheads on deployed intercontinental ballistic
missiles, submarine-launched ballistic missiles, as well as
re-entry vehicles used for testing and training.
</P>
<P>
According to the Itar-Tass, Russia has already scrapped over
800 launching pads for intercontinental ballistic missiles and
submarine-launched ballistic missiles, about 2,000 missiles, 20
nuclear submarines and more than 50 heavy bombers.
</P>
<P>
The United States has destroyed over 600 launching pads for
intercontinental ballistic missiles and submarine-launched
ballistic missiles, about 450 missiles, 22 nuclear submarines and
more than 270 heavy bombers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
