<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landmines Ban Treaty Signed in Ottawa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The landmines ban treaty
officially opened to signing here today, and Canada became the
first to put its signature on the global convention.
</P>
<P>
Some 120 countries are expected to sign the treaty today and
Thursday at the ongoing treaty-signing conference on a global ban
on landmines here.
</P>
<P>
The treaty, negotiated and adopted in Oslo, Norway, in
September, bans the use, production, stockpiling and transfer of
anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who is here for
the meeting, witnessed the first signatures of the treaty, saying
it is "a historic victory for the weak and vulnerable of our
world."
</P>
<P>
"The Ottawa Convention is a landmark step in the history of
disarmament," Annan told hundreds of delegates from government and
non-government organizations and international agencies.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that it will provide the final impetus for a
universal ban, encompassing all mine-producing and mine-affected
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Once the treaty has been signed, "we must now turn our energies
and our imaginations to the cause of mine-clearance, so that this
victory today does not become a hollow one," Annan noted.
</P>
<P>
This call was echoed by Cornelio Sommaruga, president of the
International Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Though the ban on anti-personnel mines will "save lives and
limbs," it will "do nothing to improve the plight of the hundreds
of thousands of existing victims whose needs have barely begun to
be addressed," Sommaruga said.
</P>
<P>
"In some respects banning anti-personnel mines was the easiest
of our challenges," he said. He called for more efforts and money
to be put into the clearance of some 100 million existing mines
planted worldwide and provision of adequate assistance to victims.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien announced at the signing
ceremony that his country will contribute 100 million dollars (70
million US dollars) over the next five years to help make the
treaty work, including expanded humanitarian assistance for
landmine victims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
