<HEADLINE> Somalia Still Suffers from Unusual Rains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The rains thought to be
easing by now seem to be getting even more serious especially in
the worst affected eight regions of southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to latest reports about the floods, Shabelle River
has further burst its banks to either side, east and west causing
new disasters.
</P>
<P>
The reports said, three more villages in Balad area, 30 km
north of the capital Mogadishu, have been besieged, killing 12
people. The floods have also claimed the lives of dozens of
chicken, goats and cattle in the past three days.
</P>
<P>
More than 170 villages in Middle Shabelle region are being
affected by the floods while 120 other villages remain besieged
in Lower Shabelle, Middle and Lower Jubba regions. The worst hit
areas are where the waters from the two rivers, Shabelle and
Jubba, merged in Lower Shabelle and Middle Jubba regions.
</P>
<P>
Several populated towns such as Qoryoley, Bardera, Jilib,
Jamame, Sablale, Bu'ale and Afmadow remain badly affected by the
floods.
</P>
<P>
So far, nearly 1,500 people are believed to have died in the
floods and about half a million others are made homeless where
the farms washed away by the floods exceed tens of thousands of
hectares sown with sorghum, maize, beans and sesame. 
</P>
</TEXT>
