<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grundig Television Can Switch Itself Off: Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The electronics company Grundig
has launched a range of televisions which switch off automatically
when the viewer has left the room.
</P>
<P>
Many modern TVs include standby mode, which is activated by
pressing a button on the remote-control handset.
</P>
<P>
In this mode, the picture and sound are turned off, but the set
still consumes some electricity -- a red indicator light tells you
that the set is still powered up.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that half of all TV sets in Britain are never
switched off, but left in standby mode when the owner has finished
watching.
</P>
<P>
Grundig's new sets are designed to save power and reduce the
owner's electricity bill.
</P>
<P>
According to Grundig, the new sets feature the eco-switch,
which is operated by a remote control handset and an on-screen
menu.
</P>
<P>
The viewer can decide that the set will automatically switch
off after say, 60 minutes in standby mode, and then activate the
eco-switch by pressing a button on the remote.
</P>
<P>
At the pre-set time, the eco-switch mechanically pushes the
television's power switch into the off position.
</P>
<P>
Grundig says its new system could save television owners up to
35 pounds (56 US dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
Keith Armour of the German company said, "If everyone switched
their television off at night, we could probably save enough power
to shut down a power station." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
