<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Efforts Made to Ensure Free, Fair, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government,
political parties and church organizations have been making
efforts to ensure free, fair and non-violent election campaigns
leading to the December 29 General Election in the country.
</P>
<P>
In order to regulate the behavior of all political parties and
candidates, the dissolved Seventh Parliament passed an Electoral
Code of Conduct for the country's second multi-party elections.
</P>
<P>
Prepared by Kenya's Electoral Commission (EC), the code binds
political parties to behave peacefully and avoid electoral
violence, intimidation and bribery.
</P>
<P>
Out of the 27 registered political parties in the east African
country, 21 has so far signed the code, indicating that they
would follow the code during the campaigning period and the
polling day.
</P>
<P>
It is mandatory that every political party and candidate
intending to contest the elections subscribe to the code, and
parties will not be eligible to field candidates at any level
unless at least two senior officials sign the document.
</P>
<P>
According to the code, parties are required to condemn
violence and intimidation, to avoid using or publishing
inflammatory language, to ensure that no weapons of any kind are
carried to political meetings.
</P>
<P>
The code also requires political parties to do nothing to
impede another party's access to voters for canvassing membership
and soliciting support, and to refrain from bribery and other
inducements.
</P>
<P>
Following recent incidents in which mobs stoned convoys of
opposition presidential candidates Mwai Kibaki and Raila Odinga
last month, the EC has ordered the Police Commissioner of Kenya
to investigate the incidents.
</P>
<P>
The code provides that infringement of the code can bring
penalties such as a formal warning, fines, withdrawal of air time
on the public media, prohibition against holding public meetings,
and even banning a culprit from entering a specified place.
</P>
<P>
The code empowers the Electoral Commission to bar a candidate
or party from campaigning if found guilty of encouraging
violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Kenyan Police has announced that all
presidential candidates would be provided with round-the-clock
police protection after presentation of nomination papers on
December 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
Local media pointed out that as violence had been the bane of
Kenyan politics, especially in recent years, protection of
president candidates by Kenyan police was essential for a
peaceful campaigning.
</P>
<P>
The National Convention Executive Council (NCEC), a lobby body
of opposition leaders pressing for constitutional reforms before
the General Election, announced publicly last month that it
dissociated itself from calls to disrupt the coming General
Election.
</P>
<P>
NCEC leader Kivutha Kibwana declared at a press conference
held on November 28 that "anyone who disrupts the elections will
not be doing so with the mandate of the NCEC."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the National Council of Churches of Kenya
has warned Kenyans against boycotting the elections and condemned
those threatening to unleash violence on the polling day.
</P>
<P>
The church body disclosed that it would organize a week of
peace prayers starting from December 7 to 14, which would be
followed by a "March for Peace" in all villages, towns and
cities.
</P>
<P>
At the polling day, The Electoral Commission said, journalists
will for the first time be allowed to escort ballot boxes to and
from counting halls to ensure fairness.
</P>
<P>
Previously, only agents of the candidates, election observers,
security personnel and presiding officers were allowed to
accompany the boxes.
</P>
<P>
The whole process of inspecting and sealing the ballot boxes,
closing the apertures of the boxes and sealing them, and
escorting the boxes to the counting hall remain at the presence
of all above-mentioned persons.
</P>
<P>
The Electoral Commission Chairman Z.R. Chesoni noted at a
daily briefing on December 2 that "it is the process and not
whether or not ballot boxes are transparent which will ensure
free and fair elections."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the procedure does not allow room for ballot
boxes to disappear or be introduced nor does it allow stuffing
boxes with unofficial ballot papers.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that it would be difficult to rig the elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
