<HEADLINE> Nigeria Denies Sending Warships to S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria today denied the
dispatch of three warships to Sierra Leone, saying that it was
the military junta that was making lies.
</P>
<P>
The junta, which seized power in the May 25 coup this year,
said on Tuesday the Nigerian contingent in the west African
peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) based in Liberia had sent naval
vessels to the territorial waters of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Up to Monday night, the three vessels were 70 nautical miles
off the Sierra Leonean coast, the junta said in a press
statement.
</P>
<P>
But the Nigerian military authorities have refuted the claim.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone interview with Xinhua late this afternoon,
defense spokesman Col. Godwin Ugbo said "this is a lie".
</P>
<P>
"I don't know why the junta made such lies," he said.
</P>
<P>
No plan has been made to transfer ECOMOG troops withdrawn from
Liberia under a phased pullout plan to Sierra Leone, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is up to ECOWAS (the Economic Community of West African
States) to decide," Col. Ugbo added.
</P>
<P>
The defense spokesman, however, agreed that ECOMOG is to
tighten economic sanctions and blockade on that country in a bid
to force the junta to implement the peace agreement signed last
October in Conakry, Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Under the Conakry peace plan, the junta will hand over power
to the ousted civilian government of President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah
next April.
</P>
<P>
But the junta has reportedly repudiated the accord by refusing
to disarm the national army and accept Nigeria's dominance in
ECOMOG which is mandated to monitor the peace process in Sierra
Leone.
</P>
<P>
The latest meeting between ECOWAS representatives and the
junta on the implementation of the peace plan went in deadlock
last week when agreement was not reached on such critical issues.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG Force Commander Major-general Victor Malu threatened on
Monday to increase especially military pressure on the junta to
bring the junta back to the negotiating table.  
</P>
