<HEADLINE> Turkish President Visits UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel said here today that the military agreement
between Turkey and Israel is for training cooperation, which is
not directed against other countries.
</P>
<P>
"The Turkish-Israeli agreement is just a military training
pact, not a security cooperation deal and not aimed at damaging
the interests of any other states," Demirel told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Demirel, arriving here this afternoon on a two-day visit to the
United Arab Emirates, would hold talks shortly with President
Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan.
</P>
<P>
He said Turkey would never ink any agreements that would harm
its Arab "brothers." Ankara signed two agreements on military
cooperation with Israel last year, sparked strong protest from the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Demirel blamed Arab states for baselessly accusing the
agreements of threatening their security.
</P>
<P>
"It is difficult for me to understand such explanations that
the military pact is under aims of damaging the interests of Iraq
and other (Arab) countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Demirel arrived here early Wednesday after a visit to Oman. He
was to fly home Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Arab countries have attacked Turkey, a predominantly
Muslim, but politically secular country for "betraying the
interests of the Islamic world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
