<HEADLINE> Lebanese Teachers Strike for Better Pay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese teachers from public
and private schools today staged a one-day warning strike to
protest government's failure to keep its promises and commitment
to improve their conditions.
</P>
<P>
George Saade, head of the Lebanese Teachers' Syndicate which
called the strike, said today's strike was echoed by all teachers
without exception.
</P>
<P>
A key commitment the government failed to meet is the
readjustment of salary scales and grading of jobs, which was
approved by parliament some three years ago. The government is
still unable to raise funds to enforce it.
</P>
<P>
Saade said that if the government does not respond to today's
strike for better pay, the syndicate will escalate measures and
stage a three-day strike, to be followed by an open-ended strike
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
At a news conference, Lebanese Minister of Education, Youth
and Sport, Jean Obeid, affirmed his support to teachers' demands,
which he said are legitimate.
</P>
<P>
But he said he opposed the form they have taken to voice their
grievances. Negotiations are continuing and some legal bills and
proposals have been tabled before the parliament for debate, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that there will be results before the end of this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
