<HEADLINE> Iran to Adopt 9-year Compulsory Education System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran is to adopt a 9-year
compulsory education system instead of the present 12-year system,
local newspaper Iran reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that a draft bill on the changes of education
system would soon be submitted to the Majlis (parliament) for
ratification.
</P>
<P>
According to the new system, all children at full age of five
are obliged to receive a three-stage general education which will
be free of charge.
</P>
<P>
The first stage is called "basic," with a period of two years,
the bill said, and all of those who passed the basic education
will be accepted for the second one named "essential."
</P>
<P>
During the four years in the second stage, the children will
receive trainings on reading, writing, listening and
comprehension, ethics and social behaviors and other courses.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who passed the second stage will be accepted for the
"senior" stage with a period of three years, undertaking training
on "how to choose one's desired future social life according to
the country's capability and demands."
</P>
<P>
After passing the three stages of education, the students will
receive diplomas of general education and have the right to take
part in the country's entrance examinations for higher education.
</P>
<P>
Under the present education system, children must spend five
years in primary school, three years in middle school and four
years in high school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
