<HEADLINE> U.S. Federal Reserve Says Asian Crisis Affect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
said today that American manufacturers and farmers are starting to
feel the impact of financial crisis in some Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
"Asian financial turmoil and currency weakness have adversely
affected demand for manufactured and agricultural exports," the
Fed said in its "Beige Book" report, a survey of economic
conditions by its 12 district banks.
</P>
<P>
"Some districts report increased competition from imports," it
said.
</P>
<P>
Today's report, based on information collected before November
24, proves that some economists have been worrysome over the
eventual impact on this country.
</P>
<P>
Five of the Fed's district banks which include Boston,
Philadelphia, Cleveland, Dallas and San Francisco already have
noted the affect of weakened demand from Asia. A sixth, Atlanta,
said manufacturers are scaling back production in anticipation of
weaker demand.
</P>
<P>
Two regional banks of San Francisco and Dallas said Asia's
turmoil has hurt demand for agricultural exports.
</P>
<P>
The Fed said, "virtually all regions are experiencing tight
labor markets, with some reporting increased wage pressures in
specific industries and occupations with labor shortages."
</P>
<P>
As Christmas is approaching, "retailers are generally
optimistic about the sales outlook," the report said. But they
"are having a particularly difficult time in hiring and retaining
seasonal workers."
</P>
<P>
Despite rising wages, "price pressures remain neutral on
balance," the report said. "increasing overseas competition
appears to be offsetting any effects of wage gains."
</P>
<P>
On balance, the Fed said district banks "report a continued
moderate pace of economic growth."
</P>
<P>
Today's survey will be used when the Fed policy-makers meet on
December 16 to discuss interest rates. When Asia's chaos began
spreading to world financial markets, most economists had been
predicting the central bank would lift interest rates to slow the
economy as a bid to prevent inflation. But recently, many have
said the dampening imact of Asia's proble ms could postpone any
rate increase well into next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
