<HEADLINE> AL: Sanctions on Iraq, Libya Obstruct Arab Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- A senior official of the Arab
League (AL) said today that the sanctions imposed against Iraq and
Libya are preventing the establishment of an Arab common market.
</P>
<P>
Hassan Ibrahim, secretary general of Al's Arab Economic Unity
Council Hassan Ibrahim "the Arabs are required to enhance joint
action in light of this state of affairs for realizing a tangible
Arab future."
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Libya have been suffering under the United
Nation-imposed sanctions since the early 1990s. The Arab League
has been working towards the lifting of the embargoes.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim made the remarks on the sidelines of the 66th session
of the Arab Economic Unity Council.
</P>
<P>
The Council has decided to make the Arab common market the main
concern of the current session that opened at the AL headquarters
here today. Egypt, Iraq, Libya, Syria, Jordan, Yemen and
Mauritania are the members of the council.
</P>
<P>
The meetings are expected to work out an executive protocol on
the full implementation of the common market's regulations in the
seven member countries that endorsed its formation as of January
1998, he added.
</P>
<P>
The regulations stipulate full customs exemption for all goods
and commodities flowing in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Ibrahim said that efforts are now made to set up a mini Arab
market to include the seven member states in preparation for
expanding it to cover others of the 22-member Arab League.
</P>
<P>
Other topics on the agenda include discussion of a report on
the changes in global economy, developments in the Arab economy in
1996 and Palestinian economic conditions under the Israeli
blockade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
