<HEADLINE> Study Finds Proton Beams Effective in Curing Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Researchers said today that
proton beams originally designed for use in nuclear physics
research have proven effective in curing several types of cancer.
</P>
<P>
The advantage of proton beam technology over conventional
radiation is it does no harm to surrounding tissues, researchers
told the annual meeting of the Radiological Society of North
America, which was held in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
Proton beams, produced by particle accelerators called
cyclotrons or synchrotrons, have produced better results than
conventional radiation treatment against advanced cancers of the
prostate, bone and eye.
</P>
<P>
A uniform radiation dose of the beams can be targetted at the
tumor while at the same time delivering zero dose to the healthy
tissue, scientists said.
</P>
<P>
A study of 645 men with prostate cancer at Loma Linda
University in California found proton beam therapy was as
effective as surgical removal of the prostate in curing the
cancers four years after treatment.
</P>
<P>
Proton beam treatment of a type of cancer that attacks the base
of the skull was effective for 92 percent of 180 patients,
compared to about half of patients treated with standard radiation
therapy, doctors at three Massachusetts facilities said.
</P>
<P>
An added benefit to patients who underwent proton beam therapy
was that only a small number suffered incontinence, compared to 40
percent of those who underwent the surgery. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt, Qatar Heal Rifts After Saudi Mediation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Mediated by Saudi Arabia,
Egypt and Qatar today patched up their disputes during a meeting
in Riyadh between the leaders of the two countries, the Saudi
Press Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad
Bin Khalifa Al-Thani held talks in the Saudi capital under the
sponsorship of Saudi King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in an "amicable" atmosphere and resulted
in "the return of the relations between both brotherly states back
to normal."
</P>
<P>
Reports said that the leaders of the two countries appreciated
the successful fence-mending mediation and efforts by King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-Qatari relations deteriorated in October when Egypt
was ready to boycott the fourth Economic Conference of the Middle
East and North Africa in Doha.
</P>
<P>
Qatar responded with a ban on the entry of nationals of Egypt
alongside other nine countries as a security precaution for the
Doha conference, infuriating Cairo and other Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to their row were Qatar's charges that Egypt had
plotted the 1996 coup attempt to overthrow the Gulf sheikdom's
emir. Egypt rejected the charges and demanded for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
Signals for solving the crisis came to the fore Monday as their
war of words on the media eased amid intensive mediation by Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
The reconciliation bids involved messages sent by King Fahd to
the leaders of Egypt and Qatar and visits by their foreign
ministers to Riyadh before today's summit.
</P>
<P>
Upon leaving for Riyadh, Qatar's emir expressed sorrow for
"what happened between the two countries" and said his "meeting
with Mubarak comes to erase any misunderstanding between the two
sides."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa asserted Tuesday during
his visit to Riyadh that Cairo does not want to escalate the
crisis and is keen to maintain relations with Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak and Sheikh Hamad have left Riyadh for home after their
rapprochement meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
