<HEADLINE> Xie Jun Seeks to Regain Women's Chess World Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Former world champion Xie Jun
of China is seeking to regain her world title by competing in the
international chess top-ten tournament to be started on December 9
in Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
"I'm determined to try my best to win the candidancy, but it
was a long time that I did not play such a prolonged contest," Xie
said in a phone interview from the Dutch capital.
</P>
<P>
Xie, who lost her title to Hungarian Szusza Polgar in February,
1996, added that she is looking forward to the arrival of coach Ye
Jiangchuan, who flew off Thursday from Beijing, for her thorough
preparation against different rivals in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Xie, with 2,505 ranking points, will face off nine world top
international grandmasters including Pia Cramling of Sweden with
2,527 points and Maya Chiburdanidze of Georgia with 2,525.
</P>
<P>
The 18-round tournament also includes Nana Ioseliani of Georgia
(2,504 points), Ketevan Arakhamia of Scotland (2,441) and Chinese
Peng Zhaoqin of the Netherlands (2,422).
</P>
<P>
The best seven in the satellite tournaments, the grandmaster
with best points after the seven, and the losers from the last
championship final and the candidates play-off, qualify for the
tournament which will run to December 30.
</P>
<P>
The competition features the double round-robin format with the
best two to vie for the right to challenge against defending world
champion Szasza.
</P>
<P>
Xie scored three wins and three draws against the grandmasters
with over 2,600 ranking points in August during her training in
Europe late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
