<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jobless Claims Decrease to Five-Week Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide
first-time claims for jobless benefits dropped by 3,000 in the
week ended November 29 to the lowest level in five weeks, the
U.S. Labor Department reported here today.
</P>
<P>
New applications for unemployment insurance totaled a
seasonally adjusted 303,000, a little dip from a revised 306,000 a
week earlier, according to the department.
</P>
<P>
Last week's total was the lowest since 299,000 during the week
ended October 25. Analysts believe a claims level below 320,000
reflects a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
Except for a 334,000 total on the week ended November 15, new
claims have remained below 320,000 for 13 weeks, the longest
string since a 26-week stretch ended in February 1989.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate dropped to 4.7 percent in October, lowest
since October 1973, while payrolls grew by 284,000.
</P>
<P>
During the week ended November 22, 43 states and territories
reported increases, seven registered declines and three were
unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
