<HEADLINE> French Interior Minister Defends Liberal Immigration Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- French Interior Minister
Jean-Pierre Chevenement defended the liberal immigration law he
presented to the National Assembly today.
</P>
<P>
The law met strong opposition from right-wing parties and
reserve from some leftist parties.
</P>
<P>
"France marches by absorbing, and the more it preserves its
capacity to integrate, the more it can do it," said Chevenement in
a speech at the National Assembly as it prepared to debate the law.
</P>
<P>
The law will greatly ease restrictions on immigration and stay
by foreigners in France, in contrast to immigration laws adopted
by two previous conservative governments.
</P>
<P>
"Beyond immigration, the real subject is integration," said the
minister. "The natural diversity of the French people has been
enriched since the middle of the 19th century by the contributions
from the people of Europe and the world."
</P>
<P>
The debate on immigration came one week after another liberal
law on nationality presented by the Socialist government was
adopted by the parliament. The law allows all children born of
foreign parents in France to obtain French nationality by the age
of 18.
</P>
<P>
"The process of integration, which is in the heart of the
Constitution and the conception itself of the French people,
continues," Chevenement said. It will careen through the republic
for decades to come, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
