<HEADLINE> EU to Finance Development Projects in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission -- the
European Union's executive body -- today decided to finance six
development projects in South Africa with an aid package of 107.1
million ECUs (119.6 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The funding will come from the European Reconstruction and
Development Program for South Africa, which has a budget of 500
million ECUs in grants for the period from 1996 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, the third largest recipient of the EU's financial
assistance, plans to use the fund to establish an integrated
management and planning system and a labor training system.
</P>
<P>
The EU fund will also help improve infrastructure and the
quality of working skills in local governments in two South
African provinces. In addition, it will provide regular health
care to some 300,000 of the most disadvantaged residents in the
Western Cape.
</P>
<P>
The fund will also be earmarked to build more multi-functional
sports facilities that require low maintenance in disadvantaged
areas. The sports facilities are expected to serve as focal
points for rebuilding and developing communities. 
</P>
