<HEADLINE> Article On Re-opening Cross-Straits Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- "Cross-Straits Relations"
magazine will carry an article by Xiao Zhiguang calling for
re-opening talks between the mainland and Taiwan, saying that the
mainland has taken steps to arrange this but Taiwan has refused an
invitation.
</P>
<P>
The Association for the Relations Across the Taiwan Straits
asked Taiwan's Straits Exchange Foundation to visit the mainland
without taking an explicit stand on political negotiations,
calling talks between the two a symbol of their sincerity.
</P>
<P>
Compatriots on both sides of the Taiwan Straits understand that
improving relations is a politic issue and that political
negotiations on ending the across-straits state of hostility in
accordance with the "one China" principle should be held, the
article says, and that if talks between the two avoid touching on
political issues and only focus on routine matters it is not very
practical.
</P>
<P>
From February 1996 to September 1997, Taiwan authorities
repeatedly said they would end cross-Straits hostilities by
holding negotiations, but when President Jiang Zemin called for an
end to hostilities and for negotiations in accordance with the
"one China" principle in his report at the 15th National Party
Congress, Taiwan authorities said that Taiwan should be recognized
as an "independent sovereign country," the article says.
</P>
<P>
If political negotiations begin, political differences can be
discussed according to the "one China" principle, and a solution
acceptable to both sides to economic or other general matters can
be found by avoiding politically sensitive issues, it says,
concluding that the talks between the two sides on how to proceed
with political negotiations will be conductive to future
consultations and will break the deadlock in the way of talks.
</P>
<P>
The author of the article says he hopes Taiwan authorities can
give a sincere response to Jiang's appeal and show their sincerity
about political negotiations, which depend on the attitude of
Taiwan authorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
