<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Islamic Countries Differ over Mideast Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Major differences have emerged
among the member states of the Organization of Islamic Conference
(OIC) over the hot topic of Middle East peace process although all
of them consider Israel as the biggest threat to the Muslim world.
</P>
<P>
Most of the OIC members agreed with the Middle East peace
process, sources close to the current OIC experts meeting here
told Xinhua today, but some voiced their opposition to the process
in today's discussion of the OIC political committee.
</P>
<P>
There were hot debates over the issue of Middle East peace
process this morning and big differences appeared, they said.
</P>
<P>
The OIC Experts have been working for the last three days on
draft resolutions to be reviewed by foreign ministers of the
organization and be adopted by heads of state in the Eighth OIC
Summit scheduled for December 9-11 in Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that most of the OIC members said that it was
necessary to continue the peace process to bring a lasting peace
in the region despite the hardline stance of the Israeli Likud
government towards the issue.
</P>
<P>
They believed that the only way out of the current impasse was
the implementation of the agreements reached between Israel and
the Arabs.
</P>
<P>
However, some countries held the view that there was no use to
hold talks with a state like Israel, saying that the Middle East
peace process has run into a deadlock and the Islamic countries
should seek other ways to "liberate the occupied land of the
Arabs."
</P>
<P>
Iranian deputy foreign minister and spokesman of the Eighth
OIC Summit Mohammad Javad Zarif confirmed the differences among
the OIC members over the Issue of Middle East peace process
without mentioning their names, saying that it was natural for
the OIC members to have different views.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Zarif said debates would
continue over the issue of Middle East peace process this
afternoon, reiterating that the full restoration of the legitimate
rights of the Palestinians was the only way to solve the issue.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the OIC experts have not reached agreements
over the issues of Islamic human rights and international
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
However, Zarif noted, the OIC experts have reached an agreement
over the issue of the formation of Islamic common market and
proposed to set up a special committee under the OIC to follow up
the issue.
</P>
<P>
With the development of regional economic cooperation, he said,
the OIC member states should improve their economic cooperations
in various fields.
</P>
<P>
The economic cooperation among the OIC members will help
strengthen the solidarity of the Islamic countries and improve
the south-south cooperation, he said, terming cooperation and
consultation as two major principles of the OIC.
</P>
<P>
About the issue of Iraq, Zarif said, the political committee
adopted a draft resolution with the opposition of the Iraqi
delegation.
</P>
<P>
Without specifying the draft, he said that the OIC experts
stressed the importance to safeguard the independence, sovereignty,
territorial integrity of Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
