<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiluba Urged Govt Officials to be Accountable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba today urged government officials to be accountable to the
people of Zambia or else they may be punished.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the swearing-in ceremony at the state house for
newly-appointed Vice-President Christon Tembo, defense chiefs and
other officials, Chiluba said with sadness that some ministers
are abusing their offices by not following laws and established
procedures.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said he will not tolerate any indiscipline among
ministers who want to do things in their own way.
</P>
<P>
He also warned that he will not hesitate to punish "erring"
ministers, stressing that they should be responsible to the
people who are their "real masters".
</P>
<P>
"I have no time to bargain with ministers to tell them what to
do," the president said, adding, "ministers should put aside
their pomp and pride and open up to the people they serve."
</P>
<P>
Chiluba noted that some ministers stop respecting people when
they take up office because they feel they are "bigger" than what
they are. This arrogant attitude, he argued, must be changed.
</P>
<P>
Besides Tembo, those sworn in today include Major General
Solomon Mumbi who replaced former army commander Nobby Shimbeye,
Sande Kayumba who took over the air force instead of Ron.
Shikapwasha as well as several other officials and justices.
</P>
<P>
In a major government reshuffle Tuesday which affected most of
the ministerial portfolios including the posts in the ministries
of defense and foreign affairs, Chiluba appointed Tembo as
vice-president to replace Brigade General Godfrey Miyanda.
</P>
<P>
The reshuffle, according to Chiluba, is designed to "reinforce
and rejuvenate" the cabinet following the October 28 abortive
military coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
