<HEADLINE> Maintaining Transportation Order During China's Spring Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China is preparing for the
upcoming Lunar New Year, its traditional Spring Festival, when
millions of farmers working in cities will return to their
villages for family reunions, causing serious transportation
problems, according to central departments.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo told officials at a meeting today
that orderly movement is good for social and economic development
and for ordinary people, and asked Party committees and
governments to start making arrangements.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held jointly by seven departments, including
the Ministry of Labor, the Ministry of Public Security, the
Ministry of Railways and the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Special offices should be set up to oversee the work, he said,
and governments should persuade some people to stay where they
are, while transportation departments need to do more.
</P>
<P>
For four years, the State Council has held meetings to address
this problem, with more surplus rural laborers in cities. The
central government's basic policy is to encourage these farmers to
try to find work closer to their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that cities should create more employment
opportunities, and find ways of increasing farmers' income. He
said that China will build labor markets, improve controls on this
movement, and better educate farmers and train them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
