<HEADLINE> Flood Relief Goods Arrive in E. Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Relief goods worth of 100
million Uganda Shillings (some 100,000 U.S. Dollars) have arrived
in the flood-hit Mbale district in eastern Uganda, The New Vision
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The items provided by the World Food Program include 90 bags
of maize flour, 1,400 bags of soybean flour, 30 bags of sugar,
179 bags of green peas, 100 bales of blankets, 749 saucepans and
155 cartons of soap, 1,651 jerry-cans, 15 tents and 105 cartons
of biscuits.
</P>
<P>
The relief goods will be distributed to flood victims, said
Abdu Masaba, Red Cross Mbale branch manager. The floods have
killed at least 35 people in the district.
</P>
<P>
Reports from various parts of the country also said
rain-related disaster continued to bring losses to the local
people.
</P>
<P>
Rotting bodies caused dysentery in eastern Mbale district.
Five persons have been admitted in Bududa Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Martha Gidudu, senior nursing officer of the district medical
office, said her office was working hard to keep the situation
under control. Medical supplies had been dispatched to the
affected area, she added.
</P>
<P>
Many places have been flooded in western Kabarole District. A
bridge linking towns of Fort-Portal with Bundibugyo was severely
damaged. But local police said they have not yet received any
casualty report.
</P>
<P>
In the southwest of the country, a major road linking Rwanda
and Uganda was blocked by a major landslide over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
H.R. Kibuuka, permanent secretary of the Ministry of Works,
Transport and Communications, said Kabale-Katuna road closed
temporarily and the ministry advised vehicles to and from Rwanda
to use Ntungamo-Mirama Hill-Kakitumba road. 
</P>
