<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Down to New Four-year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Falling gold prices have
driven the beleaguered Australian dollar down to a new four-year
low today.
</P>
<P>
Overnight, the Australian dollar fell to a new four-year low of
67.26 US cents. During the day's session, the Australian dollar
traded as low as 67.30 US cents, closing at 67.38 US cents.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Bank corporate exchange senior dealer Stavros
Nitis said the Australian dollar opened at 67.70 US cents, but
could not sustain that level. The currency was weighed down by
speculation of further weakness in the gold price.
</P>
<P>
"Rumors of more selling of gold by South American central banks
are causing a bit of concern in the gold prices, and that's
putting a dampener on the Aussie as well," Nitis said.
</P>
<P>
Merrill Lynch analyst William O'Neill said that the news that
Argentina sold its gold reserves is symptomatic of central bank
thinking worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's central bank confirmed in a statement earlier that
it has sold around 4 million ounces of gold -- all of the
country's non-minted gold -- in the first half of the year for
1.485 billion US dollars, or 370.22 per ounce.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, central bank deputy governor Stephen Grenville
told reporters that it was too early to assess the impact of the
Asian slowdown on Australian growth, or on monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
Against the yen, the Australian dollar finished at 86.99 from
87.06 yesterday. It was also at 1.1947 marks, from 1.2006.
</P>
</TEXT>
