<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tanzania Battered by Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Following months of
drought, Tanzania is now battered by floods as continuous rains
over the past few weeks have displaced hundreds of families and
cut off roads to thousands of people.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 families are rendered homeless when floods
destroyed their houses following torrential rains in Magu and
Geita districts here last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The floods have forced the resettlement of 186 families in
Kisesa village, and destroyed Bujora Primary School buildings and
1,116 hectares of crop in Magu, said Jomo Walae, an official with
the district council.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a 30-year-old woman, Suzi Mahebe, had her
left leg broken when her house collapsed on Sunday afternoon
following the rains which poured down for a whole day, reported
Daily News today.
</P>
<P>
The official said the affected families are in urgent need of
food and medicines.
</P>
<P>
Halima Khatib, Geita district commissioner, said the floods
have seriously affected the Nderema Village.
</P>
<P>
About 3,200 acres of maize, beans and sorghum have been washed
away, she said. A team of experts have been dispatched to the
village to assess the impact of the Sunday floods.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the Mbeya Region in southwestern Tanzania, a
40-year-old woman named Sabina Mwakyusa, and her nine-year-old
son, Hassan Fidelis Elias, died instantly when a wall of their
house collapsed following heavy rains. The woman's another child
was rescued by neighbors fortunately.
</P>
<P>
The recent floods have also blocked the traffic for 90 percent
of residents in Same District, in the northern region of
Kilimanjaro, according to The Guardian today.
</P>
<P>
The floods have caused severe landslide, damaging most roads
in the mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
What is more, the rains have made 360 kilometers of roads
impassable, cornering 203,400 residents out of a total of 226,000
in the areas.
</P>
<P>
Communication in Chome-suti, Mamba Vunta and Maore divisions
have been cut off, Kangwa said.
</P>
<P>
Seven buses from Dar es Salaam to Gonja are stranded at
Mkomazi, he added.
</P>
<P>
The rains over the past few weeks, however, have replenished
water at major dams, easing power shortages in this eastern
African country, said Tanzania Electric Supply Company Managing
Director, Baruany Luhanga Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania has been forced to adopt a power rationing system
since September because of the drought. This is the second time
for Tanzania to carry out such a system since 1993. But more
rains might change the situation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
