<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's 11th Parliament Dissolved, New Polls Planned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 4 (Xinhua)-- India's 11th Lower House of
Parliament was today dissolved ending a political uncertainty and
paving the way for fresh polls early next year.
</P>
<P>
The communique on dissolution of the House was issued by
President K.R. Narayanan shortly after he met with care-taker
Prime Minister I.K. Gujral and Finance Minister P. Chidambaram
this noon.
</P>
<P>
The president's decision came after the Cabinet unanimously
recommended Wednesday night that the House be dissolved so that a
fresh mandate could be obtained from the people.
</P>
<P>
The dissolution of the House has brought to an end nearly
one-month-long political uncertainty triggered by the Jain
Commission Interim Report on former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi's
assassination in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The report was tabled before the two Houses on November 20 by
the United Front (UF) government. Since then the normal session of
Parliament was disrupted by Congress MPs, who strongly demanded
the removal of three Cabinet ministers from the Dravida Munnetra
Kazhagam (DMK), one of the UF constituents, from the Gujral
government for its involvement in the assassination case.
</P>
<P>
The UF, however, time and again rejected Congress demand, for
it maintained that the report was just an interim one and it
needed further investigation.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Congress withdrew its support to the
government on November 28. As a minority government, the Gujral
government tendered its resignation soon afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Both the Congress Party and the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP),
the two major national parties, have expressed their desire to
form next government and asked the president to give them time
for the purpose. Yet neither of the party could muster enough
support to fulfill their wishes in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
The president signed the proclamation dissolving the House
after coming to the conclusion that "people needed a reprieve from
the political instability".
</P>
<P>
The six-page presidential communique said, "The President has
borne in mind the paramount importance of national cohesion,
political integrity and the need to ascertain the democratic will
of the people."
</P>
<P>
The 11th Lower House of Parliament, which saw three prime
ministers come and go, has had the second shortest term -- 18
months and a half in Indian history, second to the ninth House
which lasted only 15 months since December 2, 1989. A.B. Vajpayee
and Deve Gowda had to quit after losing confidence votes, and I.K.
Gujral resigned on his own after withdrawal of Congress support.
He was asked by the president to head the care-taker government.
</P>
<P>
The life of the 11th House was cut short by the inherent danger
of minority government totally depending on outside support of a
single party and having to exist in considerable unease at the
will and pleasure of the other party.
</P>
<P>
The Left and the BJP welcomed the dissolution of the House. The
Left said that this would put an end to the "horse-trading by the
BJP" and charged the Congress with plunging the country into a
crisis. The BJP said that none else but the Congress and the UF
should be held responsible for terminating the life of the present
House three and half years ahead of its tenure.
</P>
<P>
The House was constituted after the general elections held in
April-May, 1996. The Rashtriya Janata Dal today accused some UF
constituents of ignoring the financial implications of mid-term
elections and creating a situation for dissolution of the House.
</P>
<P>
the president today also issued an order that fresh elections
be completed and the new House constituted by March 15 next year.
</P>
<P>
Election Commissioner G.V.G. Krishnamurty said today that fresh
elections will be held between the third week of February and
first week of March next year.
</P>
<P>
Share prices plunged in the stock exchange market this
afternoon immediately after dissolution of the House as foreign
institutional investors and bull operators indulged in nervous
selling. Market players, who had been making speculative purchases
in the past few sessions on hopes of some solution to the
political crisis, turned active sellers at all levels pulling
scrips to recent lows.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roads Situation Improved in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Public Projects and
Housing Roberto White said Mozambique's over 8,350-km-long roads
have been repaired to different extent in the past four years and
some 12,000 km highways maintained.
</P>
<P>
White made the statement Wednesday at the third national
symposium on road and bridge maintenance, the Noticias paper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said, 350 km roads have been completely rehabilitated while
6,000 km were only under preliminary repairment. The rest of the
2,000 km are third grade roads which have been repaired mainly
under manpower.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the minister noted, only 870-km highways in the
country were in a good state, which made up of three percent of
all roads in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
Now the number reached 4,540 km, which accounts for 16 percent
of the country's roads.
</P>
<P>
White announced that 15,000-km roads will be maintained in
1998, most of which belong to dirt roads which are difficult for
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has a total of 30,000-km-long highways, 4,000 km of
which are asphalt roads. During the 16-year-long civil war, most
of the roads had been damaged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
