<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Economy Continues Export-Led Growth in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Germany's gross domestic product
(GDP) continued its export-led growth in the third quarter, rising
one percent over the previous quarter and 2.4 percent over the
same period of 1996, according to official data released today.
</P>
<P>
The growth followed a same one-percent GDP rise registered in
the second quarter from the first quarter, said the Federal
Statistics Office in Wiesbaden.
</P>
<P>
Economics Minister Guenter Rexrodt expressed welcome in Bonn to
the data, believing it raises the economic prospects for a 2.5
percent growth for 1997 as projected.
</P>
<P>
German economy rose 1.4 percent in 1996, and 1.9 percent in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The statistics office attributed the third quarter GDP rise to
continued strong exports, which grew by 13.2 percent over the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Another contributing factor was the increase in capital
equipment investments, at 5.2 percent in the third quarter, a
record since 1992.
</P>
<P>
The office also reported that in the third quarter, Germany's
labor productivity was up 3.7 percent, accompanied with a net loss
of 461,000 jobs compared to the same period last year, and a 2.4
percent drop in per-unit production costs -- the sharpest drop
since the 1990 German unification.
</P>
<P>
The gross income of employees was down 0.3 percent from the
third quarter of 1996, said the office, in contrast, corporate and
capital gains were up 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
Germany's private consumption dropped by 0.3 percent in the
third quarter, the office added.
</P>
<P>
The third quarter data released also showed a slowdown in
economy in the eastern part of the country. The real GDP growth
of the eastern part was 1.5 percent, compared with western
Germany's 2.4 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
