2552.5 points in sluggish trade.
</P>
<P>
Nevitts broker Steve Mayne said people were taking advantage of
gains made earlier in the week and were indulging in profit
taking.
</P>
<P>
"There has been profit taking across the board," he said.
</P>
<P>
The market was beginning to wind down as the Christmas period
approached and this had led to a reasonably small volume today.
</P>
<P>
The national turnover for the day was 372.75 million shares
worth 864.98 million Australian dollars (743.8 million US dollars)
with falls outnumbering rises 537 to 479.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Murdoch's News Corp was the bright spot in the market
today, soaring 5.4 percent to close 42 cents firmer.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index lost 4.7 points to 4360.9 points
today.
</P>
<P>
Telecommunications giant Telstra added two cents today, and was
the highest turnover stock with 30.374 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
The banking index fell 55.7 points to 5325.4 points with ANZ
dragging down the sector as it went ex-dividend.
</P>
<P>
ANZ shares were 49 cents cheaper while Westpac lost one cent
and Commonwealth slumped 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index dropped 15.3 points to 1111.7 points
with weaker gold and overnight commodity prices and profit taking
in the sector.
</P>
<P>
BHP plunged 36 cents, Rio Tinto slipped 15 cents, WMC lost 4.4
percent of its worth, sliding 23 cents and MIM was steady.
</P>
<P>
The gold index eased 9.4 points to 881.8 points, while the gold
price fell to 290.20 US dollars an ounce from 292.70 an ounce at
yesterday's close.  
