<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks Investor in Telecom Co. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
is still looking for an appropriate investor in the Tanzania
Telecommunication Company Limited (TTCL) which is scheduled for
privatization by 1999.
</P>
<P>
Communications and Transport Minister William Kusila told
President B. Mkapa in Songea on Tuesday that the company is lined
up for divestiture under the ongoing restructuring of parastatal
organizations, according to the Daily News today.
</P>
<P>
The president launched on that day a new telephone house
constructed in Songea at the cost of 412 million Shillings (about
660,000 million US Dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government is also exploring the probability of selling
some shares to TTCL workers, Kusila said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government has made headway in the
installation of a modern telephone network which has made
telephone communication easily accessible to many people.
</P>
<P>
The minister mentioned some of the completed telephone network
projects such as the phone lines linking Dodoma and Mwanza,
Dodoma and Dar es Salaam, and Dar es Salaam with other
municipalities and towns like Zanzibar, Pemba, Tanga, Moshi and
Arusha by installing 3,840 lines from 960 previously.
</P>
<P>
A bigger telephone exchange has been installed in Dar es
Salaam adding telephone lines to 6,000 people from 1,400.
</P>
<P>
A project to upgrade two satellite stations at Mwenge in Dar
es Salaam has been completed, which were rated at grade A, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, installation of new subscriber
trunk dial (STD) exchange has been completed in various towns in
the country raising telephone connection capacity by 62 percent
from 106,258 lines in 1991 to 173,357 lines this year.
</P>
<P>
The TTCL board chairman, Prof. Mathew Luhanga, told the
president that the southern highland regions have been accorded
priority in having major telephone projects because of their
performance in minerals development and food and cash crop
output. 
</P>
</TEXT>
