<HEADLINE> Tough Drug Tests Introduced into Weightlifting Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Weightlifting
Federation (IWF) is to introduce the toughest drug controls in the
upcoming World Weightlifting Championships to be held in Chiang
Mai on Friday.
</P>
<P>
More than 120 drug tests will be conducted during nine days of
competition which features weightlifting powerhouses of China,
Russia and Turkey, said IWF spokesman Jeno Boskovics.
</P>
<P>
China has dispatched nine women and 11 men, Russia has sent in
10 men and eight women while Turkey has seven women and 12 men for
a total of 276 men and 180 women at the Championships.
</P>
<P>
The Championships will be the last with 10 weight classes for
men and nine for women as the weightlifting tournaments will only
have eight categories for men and seven for women from next year.
</P>
<P>
The deduction made by the weightlifting authorities aims for a
leaner competition to make the sport more attractive before the
strongwomen make their debut in the Sydney Olympic Games in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
