<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Reserves Right to Use Anti-Personnel Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China will not give up the
right to use anti-personnel mines (APLs) on its own soil so as to
form defensive capabilities, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said
today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Tang Guoqiang said that in April 1996, the Chinese
government announced that China would not export APLs that failed
to meet the technical specifications of the amended Protocol even
before its formal entry into force. Currently, China is giving a
positive consideration to the early ratification of the new
Landmine Protocol.
</P>
<P>
China is one of the earliest States Parties to the Conventional
on Prohibition or Restriction on the Use of Certain Conventional
Weapons Which May Be Deemed to Be Excessively Injurious or to Have
Indiscriminate Effects (CCW) and Protocol II (Landmine Protocol)
of the CCW.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the view that the general principle on solving the
landmine problem should be one that takes balanced account of both
humanitarian concerns and the legitimate military needs of
sovereign states for self-defense," Tang said when answering a
question at a press conference this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the issue of security is in itself a
humanitarian concern. National conditions and defense needs vary
from country to country. For many countries, especially those
lacking advanced defensive weapons, APLs remain an effective means
of self-defense, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Chinese government has always pursued an
independent foreign policy of peace. The sole purpose of its using
APLs within its territory is to safeguard national unity and
territorial integrity and ensure the peaceful life of the Chinese
people. Before an alternative of APLs is found, China must reserve
the right to use APLs on its own soil so as to form defensive
capability, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman declared: "Based on the above-mentioned position,
China does not intend to sign the Convention on the Prohibition of
the Use, Stockpiling, Production, and Transfer of Anti-Personnel
Mines and on Their Destruction."
</P>
<P>
"However, we respect the sovereign choice made by these
countries reaching the Convention in Oslo and understand their
humanitarian desires and concerns," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has sent an observer delegation to the
signing conference of the Convention to be held in Ottawa, Canada,
on December 3 and the parallel roundtable on international mine
clearance and assistance.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-up: Nigeria in High Gear for State Assembly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Chang Yong )
</P>
<P>
LAGOS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Barely a week after the National
Electoral Commission of Nigeria (NECON) said all materials had
been distributed for the state assembly election this Saturday,
the police deployed officers and men to polling stations to
ensure hitch-free voting.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, the country's largest metropolis and commercial
nerve center, some 8,000 policemen have been deployed to the
3,000 polling stations.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Abubakar Tsav, Lagos State Commissioner of Police, said
on Wednesday the move is to soil the ploy of some citizens who
allegedly resolved to derail the military government's transition
to civil rule program.
</P>
<P>
He also warned on the procedure at the polls, saying a voter
must not carry two cards and that "due penalties await any
erring voter".
</P>
<P>
According to the police commissioner, the dense population of
Lagos, estimated at about 10 million, "makes it the most complex
state to control".
</P>
<P>
State Administrator Colonel Mohammed Marwa has also released
12 million Naira (about 150,000 U.S. dollars) to NECON as
logistic support for the election.
</P>
<P>
In Delta State, one of the country's major oil production
bases in the southern coast, 3,000 policemen are scheduled to
undergo training on election logistics today.
</P>
<P>
They will be deployed to the polling stations across the state
before election begins on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, NECON on Wednesday suspended the polls in four
constituencies in Warri, the oil town of the state, owing to the
fragile peace there.
</P>
<P>
Local communities went into repeated clashes over the
relocation of the local government seat from the area of one
community to another shortly after the local
government election earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The clashes claimed tens of lives and led to great economic
losses as many houses, vehicles and infrastructure facilities
were damaged.
</P>
<P>
The skirmishes also halted oil production for some time.
</P>
<P>
"Elections in the four state constituencies should be
suspended forthwith until the contentions are resolved," resident
Electoral Commissioner Musa Salihu said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Osun State in western Nigeria said on Tuesday that it would
proceed with the assembly polls in the feuding communities of Ife
and Modakeke.
</P>
<P>
Bloodshed was also triggered off by the relocation of local
government headquarters from Madakeke to Ike-Ogbo in Ile-Ife area
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
State Police Commissioner Sunday Aghedo said all the state's
1,882 polling stations will be placed under police surveillance
to nip any violent act in the bud.
</P>
<P>
The state government has ordered some 3,000 policemen to be
ready for Satursday's election. They will either be stationed in
polling stations located in troubled areas or go on motorized
patrol.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are complaints over funds by politicians and
last minute disqualification of candidates for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
But NECON officials have allayed these fears and urged them to
be orderly in their campaigns, saying the list of contestants
issued to each of the political parties and the press was the
authentic and the final one.
</P>
<P>
To make the election free and fair, at least 150 independent
foreign observers are invited to monitor the polls.
</P>
<P>
The observers, which include United States and British
nationals, will arrive in the country today and head straight for
Abuja, where they will be accredited for the exercise by
officials of the foreign ministry and NECON.
</P>
<P>
As for the last minute preparations, the NECON resident
electoral commissioner to Lagos State said, "Hopefully before
Friday, everything will be in place and by Saturday morning, we
will be ready for the election."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
