<HEADLINE> China, Philippines Making Progress on Environmental Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Both China and the Philippines
are satisfied with their progress in environmental protection in
the South China Sea, Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang Guoqiang said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question at a press conference, Tang said the two
sides have reached agreement on carrying out three cooperative
projects at the second meeting of the Sino-Philippine specialist
group on oceanic environmental protection in the South China Sea
held in Manila November 12-15.
</P>
<P>
The three projects -- "red tide", "ocean pollution" and "storm
surge" -- will be implemented in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The specialist group was set up in accordance with the common
ground that the foreign ministries of the two countries reached
through negotiation in March of 1996. The first meeting of the
specialist group was held in Beijing in March this year.
</P>
<P>
Tang said the two sides are satisfied with the progress made by
the specialist group.  
</P>
</TEXT>
