<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France's GDP Grows by 0.9 Percent in Third Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- France's gross domestic product
(GDP) grew by 0.9 percent in the third quarter over the second
quarter, and by 2.7 percent over the same period last year, the
state statistics study center INSEE said today.
</P>
<P>
France has been experiencing quarterly GDP growth since the
beginning of this year. The country's GDP grew by 0.3 percent in
the first quarter, and by 1.1 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
If the rhythm of growth remains slack in the fourth quarter,
the overall GDP growth for 1997 will be 2.3 percent over last
year, against a 2.2 percent prediction by the government, said
INSEE.
</P>
<P>
Domestic demand grew by 1.2 percent in the third quarter,
compared with a 0.5 percent growth in the second quarter and a
drop of 0.4 percent in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Household consumption grew by 1.1 percent, compared with 0.1
percent in the previous quarter, while investments by enterprises
grew by 1.9 percent after a 0.4 percent rise in the previous
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Total investments, including those by households, government
and enterprises, rose by 1.7 percent in the third quarter, while
investment by households in housing increased by 3 percent after a
0.3 percent drop in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
Imports grew by 3.7 percent in the third quarters, more than
the 2.4 percent growth of exports. Purchase of professional
equipments from abroad increased by 9.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Enterprise stocks increased by 1.8 billion francs (300 million
U.S. dollars), contributing to 0.2 percent of the growth of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Manufactured production increased by 1.2 percent in the third
quarter, after a 3.1 percent growth in the previous
quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
