<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Customs Cracks Down on Smuggling of Falcons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A tourist from Bangladesh, who
tried to carry 32 falcons out of China, has been seized by Beijing
Customs officers.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the Beijing Customs Office announced today that
this is the fourth case involving smuggling of falcons that has
been smashed since September, with the total number of falcons
reaching 94.
</P>
<P>
Hossain, the seized tourist, reportedly put the falcons in four
suitcases. Six falcons had died from suffocation when the cases
were opened by customs officers.
</P>
<P>
Falcons, a rare bird under second-class state protection,
mainly live in northwestern parts of China.
</P>
<P>
A trained falcon can be sold for 10,000 to 100,000 U.S. dollars
in some foreign countries and regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
