<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Releases Two Iranian Prisoners of War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 4 (Xinhua) -- An Iraqi Foreign Ministry
spokesman said that Iraq released two Iranian prisoners of war
(POWs) this morning.
</P>
<P>
The official news agency INA said the two Iranians were
arrested in 1991 in Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
They were handed over to Iranian authorities under the
supervision of the International Committee of the Red Cross, said
INA.
</P>
<P>
The release was ordered by President Saddam Hussein "in
expression of Iraq's sincere willingness to settle pending issues
with Iran, particularly in relation to humanitarian matters."
</P>
<P>
This also reflected Iraq's "principled policy based on
establishing good relations with world states in general, and
neighbors in particular," said INA.
</P>
<P>
The release came only days ahead of the convening of the eighth
Islamic summit in Tehran, Iran in which Iraqi leaders are expected
to participate, and apparently in response to an Iranian
initiative.
</P>
<P>
Iran released some 500 Iraqi POWs a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The POW issue has long been a sticky point in improving
bilateral relations since the two countries ended their eight
years of brutal war in 1988. Each side accuses the other of
withholding POWs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
