<HEADLINE> China Seeks Unprecedented Feat in Asian Women Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Five-straight-time champion
China is seeking a unique sixth title in a row at the 11th Asian
Women's Soccer Championship to be kicked off here tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Without any ups and downs, the odds-on favourites will surely
accompolish the unprecedented feat, said Chinese team manager Jing
Zhengming.
</P>
<P>
"We should not have any major problems in winning the
Championship at home turf," Jing told the reporters.
</P>
<P>
Posing any threat to China's ambition are both DPR Korea and
Japan, which have five Asian Championship Cups, two Asian Games
Cups and an Atlanta Olympic silver plate in their trophy cabinet,
said Jing.
</P>
<P>
"China is ready for tough challeges from both Japan and DPR
Korea, but we enjoy our measurable advantages," Jing said.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, China will initiate its defending voyage with a
crucial match against DPR Korea, which Jing values as a potential
pivotable clash in Group B which also includes outsiders of the
Philipines and Uzbekistan.
</P>
<P>
The last time that China took on the Koreans, who have been
mysteriously described as unpredictable, dated back to June, 1996
when China earned a 2-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
The DPR Koreans, who have been absent from the international
arena ever since, further condense their mystique as their coach
Myong Tong Chan parried any question from reporters after their
close-door practice here.
</P>
<P>
Jing believed the DPR Koreans enjoy the calibre of entering the
last four along with three seeded squads of China, Chinese Taipei
and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The top three squads of the tournament will qualify for the
third World Women's Soccer Championship to be held in the United
States in two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
