<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hani Killers Acted on Behalf of CP, Says CP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The killers of South
African Communist Party (SACP) leader Chris Hani had acted on
behalf of right-wing Conservative Party (CP), CP leader Ferdi
Hartzenberg said.
</P>
<P>
It could be argued that Hani's murder had served the CP's
cause, South African Press Association quoted him as telling the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission in Pretoria Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Hartzenberg was testifying in the amnesty hearing of former CP
parliament member Clive Derby-Lewis and Polish immigrant Janusz
Walus, who were convicted of the April 1993 assassination of Hani
outside his Boksburg home near Johannesburg International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
Both are serving life sentences. They are seeking amnesty for
the crime on the grounds that it was politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
Hartzenberg told the commission's Amnesty Committee that the
CP had never distanced itself from Derby-Lewis, even after his
conviction for the murder. Instead, it started a fund to pay for
his legal costs.
</P>
<P>
He said the killers could have interpreted party leaders'
militant talk at the time as a sanction to use violence to
promote the CP's aims.
</P>
<P>
"I said some strong things myself which could have been
interpreted as an instruction to do something," Hartzenberg said.
</P>
<P>
The CP viewed Derby-Lewis' act in the same way as the African
National Congress reacted to the planting of a bomb by an ANC
cadre in a Durban restaurant a few years ago. The explosion
claimed the lives of nine people.
</P>
<P>
The CP approached the Hani killing in the same way,
Hartzenberg said. The country was plagued by violence at the
time, and political murders were commonplace.
</P>
<P>
In 1993, the option of achieving the CP's aims through
political ways was being eroded by agreements between the ANC and
the National Party, Hartzenberg said. There was little doubt in
the CP's mind that South Africa was heading for a one-party state
governed by the ANC/SACP alliance.
</P>
<P>
"We wanted to avoid living in such a dispensation, and
realized we will have to walk our own road of freedom. We were
living in a violent society and knew we would have to defend
ourselves."
</P>
<P>
"Hani was enemy number one of the Afrikaner," Hartzenberg
said.
</P>
<P>
Hani had obtained the second highest number of votes in the
policy-making National Executive Committee of the ANC, and one
could assume he would succeed Nelson Mandela as president,
Hartzenberg said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
