<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adds 174 Scientists to List of Academicians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China's two academic giants
announced here today that they have added 174 scientists to the
country's academic list, increasing the number of academicians to
1,015.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) has elected 58 new
academicians this year, most of whom work in basic scientific
research and fields closely connected with national economic
growth.
</P>
<P>
The age of the new academicians averages 60.9 years, and the
two youngest newly elected members are 43. The election increases
the CAS members to 610 and reduced the average age of the
CAS' academicians by one year to 69.9.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) has added 116
academicians, with one elected from the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region for the first time.
</P>
<P>
More have been elected from scientists working on major
projects such as the Three Gorges Dam and marine oil development.
</P>
<P>
The CAE has stressed the attention to experts working at the
forefront of production, with seven scientists working in
factories among those elected.
</P>
<P>
The age of the CAE's new academicians averages 64.5 years; the
youngest is 50. The election has increased the CAE membership to
439.
</P>
<P>
The two academies elect new academicians once every two years,
with no more than 60 added to the CAS and no more than 120 to the
CAE. China has 34 scientists belonging to both of the academies.
</P>
<P>
The youngest academician in the country is Che Chi-ming, 39,
from Hong Kong University.  
</P>
</TEXT>
