<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders Unilateral Ceasefire With Leftist Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel Ramos
today ordered a 30-day unilateral suspension of military
offensives against the leftist rebel group, the New People's Army
(NPA), during the Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
The unilateral ceasefire will take effect from December 6, 1997
to January 4, 1998 and may be extended for another 30 days
depending on any positive development, according to an order
signed by Ramos.
</P>
<P>
However, the order said that the ceasefire will not cover
normal law enforcement functions.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire shall by itself be a "safe-conduct pass" to all
insurgents during the period covered provided that they do not
carry their firearms, explosives and other deadly weapons, Ramos
said.
</P>
<P>
The Armed Forces of the Philippines and the Philippine National
Police are under orders to respect the ceasefire order.
</P>
<P>
The ceasefire will also provide a conducive climate for the
resumption of peace negotiations between the government and the
NPA's political wing National Democratic Front (NDF) in the
Netherlands on December 8.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Fortunato Abat earlier recommended to the
president the unilateral ceasefire as part of the government's
sincere effort for the resumption of peace talks with the NDF.
</P>
<P>
Abat said the military has accepted a proposal by the NPA to
stop temporarily military operations for 48 hours after the
release of a police officer and an army master sergeant held
captive by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
He expected that the NPA would release on Friday the two
hostages who were captured on October 30 when about 40 NPA rebels
raided the town of Rodriguez in the southern province of Rizal.
</P>
<P>
The government suspended the peace negotiations with the NDF
following the capture of the two hostages.
</P>
<P>
The NDF, the political arm of the Communist Party of the
Philippines, has fought the government for more than three decades
in some areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
Military statistics estimated that from a high of 25,600 NPA
fighters in 1986, the number of the NPA members has gone down to
5,000 as of November 30 this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
