<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Urges ECOWAS to Lift Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's military ruler
today appealed to Sani Abacha, chairman of Economic Community of
West African States (ECOWAS), to lift the sanction and embargo
imposed on his country by the regional leaders.
</P>
<P>
The foreign affairs officials quoting a letter by Major Johnny
Paul Koroma to the ECOWAS, expressing his "grave concern over the
afflictions on the ordinary Sierra Leoneans."
</P>
<P>
"Since the Conakry Agreement (on October 23) has mandated the
(military) government to continue to govern and conduct the
affairs of state without hindrance for a period of six months,
the sanction and embargo should be lifted," said Koroma.
</P>
<P>
"The health and welfare of the citizens is our direct
responsibility and Sierra Leoneans are now looking up to us as a
government to fulfill their needs and basic requirements," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Koroma went on saying, "the continuing imposition of sanction
and embargo on all commodities entering Sierra Leone makes
neither sense, nor can it be in the interest of peace and the
ordinary people of Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
"The people of Sierra Leone cannot be expected to survive for
six months without imports of food, fuel and medicine," Koroma
noted.
</P>
<P>
According to the letter, public and private transportations
are "slowly grinding to a halt due to the non availability of
petrol; the masses are forced to walk long distances to earn
their livelihood; the prices of all basic goods have been more
than doubled and drug and health services are becoming
increasingly inaccessible."
</P>
<P>
Farmers and other producers of perishable items "cannot get
their produce to the markets, the national electrical power
generation is at a standstill and (there is) a pending inability
to treat any water at all in the very near future," he added.
</P>
<P>
Koroma argued in the letter that lives of many Sierra Leoneans
have been placed at stake by what looks like an indiscriminate
and arbitrary imposition of sanction that is well destined to
brutalize the people of Sierra Leone through starvation and
disease.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said it is doubtful whether the letter will
make any impact on ECOWAS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
