<HEADLINE> Motorola to Build Multi-Billion-Dollar New Chip Complex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Motorola Inc. plans to
build a historic chip complex at West Creek in Goochland County,
Virginia, according to a press release from the company today.
</P>
<P>
The West Creek complex represents the largest single initial
investment in the history of Motorola, said Rovert Galvin,
chairman of Motorola's executive committee.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of construction, scheduled in the second
quarter of 1998, includes five buildings which are about the size
of 31 football fields in total.
</P>
<P>
Motorola, with sales revenue of 28 billion U.S. dollars in
1996, will spend about 3 billion dollars on the first phase of the
huge complex which is expected to install manufacturing equipment
by late 1999 and ship its first products by mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
With its major sites in Illinois, Arizona and Texas, Motorola
Inc. is one of the world's leading providers of wireless
communications equipment and semiconductors, as well as advanced
electronic systems, components and services.
</P>
<P>
The West Creek facility will be capable of manufacturing many
types of semiconductors -- the electronic circuits that are used
in personal computers, pagers, cellular telephones, automobiles
and microwave ovens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
