<HEADLINE> HK Business Summit Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The annual Hong Kong Business
Summit opened here today to discuss the recent currency-market
turmoil, review Hong Kong's economic changes after the handover
and forecast its business challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the one-day meeting, sponsored by the Hong Kong
General Chamber of Commerce and attended by hundreds of key local
business people, Administrative Secretary of the Hong Kong Special
 Administrative Region (SAR) Anson Chan said that "the gloomy
predictions about the 'death of Hong Kong' have not come true."
</P>
<P>
"The facts are that the key ingredients of our success story
remain firmly rooted in Hong Kong," she said. "No one present here
today, I hope, will disagree with me that the transition of Hong
Kong has gone well -- that was not the view held by many people
six months ago."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong returned to China on July 1, after 156 years of
British rule. And the SAR is exactly 156 days old.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting entitled by "Hong Kong: 156 Years and 156 Days",
Chan also expressed her optimism in Hong Kong's future, noting
that her optimism "is not based on blind faith, but on objective
facts."
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the leading Hong Kong businessmen, Deputy Chief
 Executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority Norman Chan
said: "As Hong Kong enters into a new era under the framework
of 'one country, two systems' and 'Hong Kong people governing
Hong Kong,' our attention has recently been focused on the
financial turmoil in the region and its effects on Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong, given its sound fundamentals, robust monetary and
banking system, huge foreign reserves, flexibility and resilience
in coping with external shocks, would be the first economy to
rebound after this episode, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chan stressed the need to keep confidence that, while in the
short run the markets may become more volatile or they may
overshoot from time to time and there may be pain involved during
the adjustment process, economic fundamentals should prevail in
the end.  
</P>
</TEXT>
