<HEADLINE> Liberian President Visits Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Liberian President Charles
Taylor is scheduled to wind up his two-day official visit to
Nigeria today.
</P>
<P>
Taylor arrived at the Nigerian capital of Abuja on Wednesday
against the background of reported soured relations between his
government and the west African peacekeeping force (ECOMOG).
</P>
<P>
Details of the issues being discussed are to be known but
observers noted leaders of the two countries would X-ray the
brewing threat to the existing relations between Liberia and
Nigeria on one hand and Liberia and ECOMOG on the other hand.
</P>
<P>
Taylor was reported recently as warning ECOMOG force commander
Victor Malu not to exceed his mandate during the
process of restructuring the Liberian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
According to the Abuja peace plan, ECOMOG is to help the
Liberian government to re-build and train the post-war army, but
Taylor was reported as saying his government would go ahead by
itself.
</P>
<P>
Taylor also ordered ECOMOG to quit Liberia and not to use
Liberian territory to launch attacks on the recalcitrant military
junta in neighboring Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
On the Sierra Leone issue, Taylor also reportedly asked the
international community during his visit to Guinea last weekend
to allow the crisis to be solved within the framework of a former
treaty signed among Liberia, Guinea and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said, the alleged feud between Taylor and Malu may
have been responsible for the increasing hysteria among Nigerians
in Liberia with their reported harassment by Liberian security
agents.
</P>
<P>
The alleged harassment led to the fleeing of over 3,000
Nigerians back to the country last week.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, ECOMOG began last Monday to withdraw from Liberia
under a phased pullout program in line with the Abuja Peace
Agreement.
</P>
<P>
A communique is expected before the end of Taylor's visit,
which is the third since the former warlord became president in
August this year. 
</P>
