<HEADLINE> 90 Percent of Thailand's Debt for October Rolled over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 90 percent of
Thailand's short-term foreign debts which came due in October will
be rolled over, according to the Nation daily today.
</P>
<P>
Foreign creditors have agreed to roll over about 6.3 billion
U.S. dollars' worth of credit extended to the Thai private sector.
The total debts matured in October amounted to 7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to Bank of Thailand figures, Thailand's total foreign
debts coming due within one year amount to 39 billion dollars. Of
the total, 37 billion dollars are of short-term debt.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the 7 billion dollar debt which came due in October,
an additional 5 billion dollars and 6 billion dollars came or will
come, due in November and December respectively.
</P>
<P>
However, the central bank did not say how much would be rolled
over for those two months.
</P>
<P>
The roll-over plan for October was revealed by the central bank
 Wednesday to soothe investor fears after the Thai currency hit an
all-time low of 43.05 to the U.S. dollar Wednesday afternoon. The
baht closed at 42.55 to the dollar, having lost about 63 percent
of its value to the dollar since its float in early July.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Central Bank Governor Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi
Wednesday quashed rumors that Thailand would stop paying its debts
and declare a debt moratorium.
</P>
<P>
He said that a debt moratorium was "not being considered at
all," adding that pressure for Thai companies to repay their debts
will ease early next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
