<HEADLINE> India's Lower House of Parliament Dissolved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 4 (Xinhua)-- Indian President K.R.
Narayanan today dissolved the Lower House of Parliament.
</P>
<P>
The President's decision came after the care-taker Cabinet
unanimously recommended Wednesday night that the House be
dissolved so that a fresh mandate could be obtained from the
people.
</P>
<P>
The dissolution has brought to an end nearly a month-long
political crisis triggered by the Jain Commission Interim Report
on former prime minister Rajiv Gandhi's assassination in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The report was tabled before the two Houses on November 20.
</P>
<P>
As soon as it was tabled, the Congress MPs immediately stood up
and demanded the removal of three ministers of the Dravida
Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK), one of the constituents of the United
Front, from the Gujral government. But the demand was rejected by
the United Front.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Congress, the main supporter of the Gujral
government, withdrew its support to it on November 28.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, the Gujral government resigned.
</P>
<P>
The new Lower House is expected to be formed by mid-March next
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
