<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 09:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Borrow Heavily on Foreign Currencies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese cabinet has approved an
economic reform package that includes a controversial borrowing of
up to 2 billion U.S. dollars in foreign currency, a press report
said today.
</P>
<P>
The report said the 28-point plan, ushering in across-the-board
austerity measures, was endorsed overwhelmingly in a cabinet
session Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
The projected huge foreign borrowing - long-term, lower
interest loans in a basket of foreign currencies - is to cover the
perpetual post-war budget deficit and reduce local debts, thus
helping the country out of the financial straits.
</P>
<P>
The plan was worked out and agreed upon by Lebanese President
Elias Hrawi, House Speaker Nabih Berry and Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri after successive rounds of hard negotiations among them
late November.
</P>
<P>
After the cabinet session, Hariri explained to reporters that
the decision to borrow foreign currency is considered out of its
lower interest rates than local currency loans.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate on local currency could amount to between 16
to 18 percent as against half this rate on French Franc or U.S.
dollar loans, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that local loans had to be repaid much earlier
than long-term foreign debt. It usually takes a maximum of two
years before local debts should be repaid while foreign currency
loans can last as long as 10 years.
</P>
<P>
At present, Lebanon's national debt has reached 13 billion
dollars and deficit has climbed to 60 percent of the gross
domestic product, overshooting the forecast 36 percent in early
this year's budget.
</P>
<P>
Hariri disclosed that the government's ultimate aim was to
ensure that local debts don't exceed 50 percent of the
government's overall borrowings.
</P>
<P>
Now the government's local obligations account for nearly 80
percent of the overall debt.
</P>
<P>
However, some economists and parliament members disagreed with
the plan, saying the borrowing will not be able to solve the
radical problem and no doubt have negative effects on future
generations.
</P>
<P>
The plan must go to the parliament for debate along with the
government's austerity state budget bill for 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: IMF Rescue Entails Painful Restructuring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 4 (Xinhua) -- With the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) bailout loan to help overcome its financial crisis, the
South Korean economy will face a painful restructuring, which
could bring about massive layoffs, soaring inflation, slashed
capital spending and more closings or mergers and acquisitions in
financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The 55-billion-dollar IMF rescue package will help South Korea
dodge the financial crisis in meeting its external debt
obligations and easing foreign exchange crunch.
</P>
<P>
However, because the IMF has attached harsh conditions to the
bailout, drastic and painful changes will be inevitable in the
years to come, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Letter of Intent signed by Seoul and the IMF is known to
contain four parts: fiscal retrenchment, an earlier-than-scheduled
opening of the capital market, improvement in the management of
large conglomerates and stringent financial reforms including the
restructuring of troubled financial companies.
</P>
<P>
First of all, a long-running business downturn is in store,
coupled with soaring unemployment, high interest rates and heavier
taxes.
</P>
<P>
The IMF's demand to trim the economic growth rate to three
percent for next year will cause the jobless rate to surge above
six percent, sending more than one million people out of work.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal retrenchment will in turn push up money market rates for
a long period of time. A 10-percent cut in government spending
will lead to curbs of rural development projects, infrastructure
layout and education investments.
</P>
<P>
Significant tax rises will bring about deep concerns about a
business slowdown and inflation.
</P>
<P>
These demands will also bring drastic changes to the country's
trading, finance and corporate sectors. More than anything else, a
financial Big Bang has become a reality.
</P>
<P>
In the financial sector, foreign takeovers of domestic banks
and other financial institutions will be possible, raising fears
that the outdated financial industry might be dominated by
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
With the raising of foreign stock ownership ceiling and the
earlier opening of the short-term bond market, the financial
market will be exposed to the rapid movement of hot money on a
full scale. Should another currency crisis attack the country
again, its upheavals will be greater.
</P>
<P>
Trade regime is expected to change. Some import restrictions
will be abolished and local carmakers and other companies will
face full blown competition from foreign manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Business conglomerates will be forced to adjust to the new
management environment under the agreement, which mandates
stricter disclosure rules and accounting regulations and sharper
cuts in debts.
</P>
<P>
For most part, analysts say, the conditions attached to the
package are badly needed if the country's outdated economic system
is to be brought in line with international standards. In fact,
many of the IMF conditions are in line with the economic policies
being implemented by the government.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read after the signature of the agreement
Wednesday, Deputy Prime Minister Lim Chang-yuel said that these
reform measures will have great impact on the economy, but the
country will be able to recover a normal growth rate and post a
surplus in international payments as from the year 2000 if they
are successful. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
