<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Head: Japan's Economy at Standstill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The head of Japan's Economic
Planning Agency (EPA) admitted today that the country's economy is
in a worse state than the government has been maintaining.
</P>
<P>
"It's appropriate to just say the economy is at a standstill
without adding such phrases like 'in the process of recovery' as
the government used to do," EPA Director General Koji Omi told a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
The EPA has been saying in its monthly reports since February
1996 that the economy is heading for recovery.
</P>
<P>
Japan's economy has been slowing down since April, following
the consumption tax hike from three percent to five percent.
</P>
<P>
Citing recent economic data showing sluggishness, including the
gross domestic product (GDP) figures for the July-September period
announced Wednesday, Omi said that the state of economy is
becoming severer.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the GDP data for the second quarter of fiscal 1997,
which showed growth of only 0.8 percent from the previous quarter,
or at an annualized rate of 3.1 percent, Omi said the figures were
slightly worse than he had expected.
</P>
<P>
Japan's economic growth rate for the fiscal year, which ends
next March, will be less than one percent, far below the
government's target of 1.9 percent, Omi said.
</P>
<P>
It would be the first time since fiscal 1994 that Japan's
economic growth rate falls below one percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
