<HEADLINE> Minister: Turkey to Improve Its Human Rights Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish government is
determined to double its efforts to improve its controversial
human rights record in the coming year, a senior official has
said.
</P>
<P>
State Minister Hikmet Sami Turk, who is responsible for
human rights affairs, made the remark in an exclusive interview
with local newspaper Daily News, which is published today.
</P>
<P>
Turk said that the Human rights Coordination Board under
the Cabinet has already worked out a series of measures aimed
at making some positive changes in human rights.
</P>
<P>
These measures include those of fighting government corruption
and restricting the alleged "uncontrollable elements" in the
state organs, he added.
</P>
<P>
The authorities concerned have started human rights courses in
schools of various levels so as to give them a better
understanding of the importance of human rights, Turk said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has reportedly singed with Britain an agreement on
human rights education among police and prison staff, who are
often accused of human rights violation by Western countries and
organizations.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is willing to cooperate with all friendly countries
in the sector of improve human rights," the state minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Turk also said that the Turkish General Staff would pay
more attention to the human rights situation in southeastern
Turkey, where the government troops have been fighting the
outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party rebels.
</P>
<P>
"Respect for human rights should not be neglected, even when
the struggle against terrorism continues," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the criticism of Turkey's human rights by European
countries, Turk stated that these countries should take an
impartial position on this issue.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has been urging Turkey to improve its human
rights situation, which is as a major obstacle to Ankara's bid
for full EU membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
