<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Companies Bullish over Business in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- American companies have a
very positive medium-term outlook for Hong Kong's business
environment against the backdrop of the recent economic turbulence
in the region, a survey showed today.
</P>
<P>
Over 96 percent of the respondents expressed a "very favorable"
or "favorable" view of Hong Kong's business environment over the
next ten years, as revealed by the results of the 1997 American
Chamber of Commerce (AmCham) business confidence survey.
</P>
<P>
The level remained unchanged from last survey.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly we're quite surprised to see such a high rate... and I
think there are a couple of reasons and very significant messages
that come out of this," Vice Chairman of AmCham Jeffrey Muir told
a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Number one is that, "it indicates a very strong, positive vote
for how the transition is being handled. American companies have
found the transition has gone ahead even better than imagined,"
said Muir.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the high level came out against the
economic turbulence in the region, since the survey was conducted
between October and November.
</P>
<P>
He listed the major reasons as the following: the impact of the
regional situation has yet to be felt by Hong Kong, and the
turbulence also bears a positive element, that is, reduction in
rental costs in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
As in previous years, maintenance of the rule of law and free
flow of information ranked as the most important factors in
assessing Hong Kong's future as a center for international
business and finance.
</P>
<P>
For the next three years, 97 percent of American companies
anticipate their business performance to be "good" or
"satisfactory". Over 55 percent intend to expand operation in
Hong Kong while 39 percent would conduct business as usual.
</P>
<P>
The survey results confirmed that Hong Kong will remain the
preferred location for regional headquarters for AmCham member
companies. For companies with regional headquarters in Hong Kong,
89 percent will retain Hong Kong as their regional center.
</P>
<P>
Less than 2 percent said they plan to relocate their regional
office, with Shanghai being a preferred choice.
</P>
<P>
The results also reflected a positive view toward commercial
prospects on the Chinese mainland. The successful summit between
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and his U.S. counterpart Bill
Clinton, and the improved bilateral relationship are expected to
benefit American businesses.
</P>
<P>
Over 94 percent of the respondents believe the outlook for the
business climate over the next five years is positive. Some 72
percent of AmCham member companies currently have operations on
the mainland compared with 56 percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The survey results suggested this trend is likely to continue.
</P>
<P>
The annual survey, entering its eighth year in 1997, was
conducted by ACNielsen-Survey Research Hongkong, a professional
survey firm, on behalf of the leading chamber of commerce in Hong
Kong, from October 6 to November 14.
</P>
<P>
A total of 560 companies responded by mail or fax, representing
a satisfactory response rate of 51 percent, said AmCham President
Frank Martin.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
