<HEADLINE> 10,000 Australian Firefighters Preparing for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 bushfires
continued to burn throughout the New South Wales (NSW) state today
as up to 10,000 firefighters and thousands of other emergency
officials and volunteers prepared for a two-day resurgence of
searing temperatures and strong winds.
</P>
<P>
NSW Rural Fire Service (RFS) Commissioner Phil Koperberg said
in Sydney the forecast change in the summer weather from today's
milder conditions meant the state would be on "full alert"
tomorrow, with all urban and rural fire crews on standby.
</P>
<P>
"The Bureau of Meteorology has briefed us this morning to the
effect that we're going to have two adverse days Friday and
Saturday before the passage of some unstable air," Koperberg was
quoted by the Australian Associated Press (AAP) as saying.
</P>
<P>
About 8,000 and 10,000 firefighters would be placed on standby
tomorrow to fight any major outbreaks around the state, compared
with the 6,000 so far brought into action in the state in
southeast Australia.
</P>
<P>
A total of 400,000 hectares had been burnt out across the
state, with 62 fires still out of control and another 111 either
under control or contained, the RFS said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Despite today's milder weather and considerable success in
containment work, no significant progress had been made in putting
out any of the state's major blazes.
</P>
<P>
"We're now into day eight of this operation and we've very
little sign of any significant relief," Koperberg said.
</P>
<P>
There were grave concerns that the Lithgow fires, which claimed
lives of two firefighters Tuesday, and blazes in the Hawkesbury
area to Sydney's northwest could merge to form a disastrous front,
but Koperberg said all efforts were being focused today to avoid
that situation.
</P>
<P>
In the Coonabarabran area of northern NSW, thousands of
firefighters, including dozens recruited from the Queensland state
nearby, continued to battle the state's biggest blaze today.
</P>
<P>
More than 170,000 hectares of bushland as well as a third of
the Pilliga scrub between Coonabarabran and Narrabri had been
burnt out by this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Visiting the area, NSW Premier Bob Carr said the worst was not
yet over, with firefighters bracing for 50 kilometers per hour
winds and dry conditions forecast for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"That combination of high winds, high temperatures and low
humidity is what we are all dreading in this region as Saturday
approaches. So let's all pray for a break in the weather," he
said.
</P>
<P>
In another development, firefighters in the Western Australia
state, western Australia, today claimed victory over a series of
bushfires that burnt out more than 400,000 hectares, AAP said.
</P>
<P>
The fires, ignited by lightning since Friday, created one of
the largest bushfire crises seen in the state's north.
</P>
<P>
An area of national park and cattle country was ravaged 200 km
north to south and 250 km east to west.  
</P>
</TEXT>
