<HEADLINE> Thailand to Step Up Crackdown on Illegal Alien Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will step up crackdown
on illegal foreign workers, and unskilled foreign laborers will
not get their work permits renewed, so as to preserve jobs for
Thai people.
</P>
<P>
Some research agencies have forecast that by the end of the
year, about a million Thai people would have lost their jobs as a
result of the economic crunch and factory and construction site
closures.
</P>
<P>
The Thai labor and social welfare and interior ministries will
cooperate to work out measures to deal with the illegal labor
problem, according to a source at the Labor Ministry today.
</P>
<P>
Ss for those legal unskilled foreign workers, numbering
300,000, their work permits will not be renewed when they expire
next year, except for those working in the fields where there are
still labor shortages, according to Labor and Social Welfare
Minister Trairong Suwannakhiri.
</P>
<P>
Companies found hiring illegal immigrants could face shutdown,
Trairong said.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago when the Thai economy was still good, the Thai
government, in spite of strong opposition from labor
organizations, allowed the use of cheap foreign labor, mostly from
Myanmar, Cambodia and Laos.
</P>
<P>
The decision had resulted in an influx of illegal foreign
workers, who are willing to do hard work with low pay.
</P>
<P>
Official estimate puts the number of illegal foreign workers in
the country at about one million.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
