<HEADLINE> Pak GDP Growth Rate to Increase by 2.9 Percent: Aziz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's growth rate of the
Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is expected to increase by 2.9
percent to 6 percent in the 1997-98 fiscal year starting from July
1, Finance Minister Sartaj Aziz said here today.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made these remarks while inaugurating a roundtable
conference organized by the Economist Conference of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate will increase mainly on account of 5 percent
growth in agriculture and 7.2 percent growth in manufacturing
sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, inflation rate will come down from 11.8 percent to 9
percent, budget deficit from 6.2 percent to 5 percent of the GDP,
and current account deficit from 6.5 percent to 5.3 percent of the
GDP, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the government will soon launch a
new phase of the reforms aimed at consolidating the gains and
breaking new grounds.
</P>
<P>
This will include areas such as investment for value-added
product exports, expansion of infrastructure, improvement in labor
laws and deeper administrative reforms, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He said that preparations were also underway for launching
"Pakistan 2010 Program" and the Ninth Five-Year Plan to provide a
longer term vision for the advancement of the nation.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that in a fast globalizing scenario, the
emphasis would have to be on ensuring competitiveness for goods
and services in the world market.  
</P>
</TEXT>
