<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Continue Trade Liberalization, Privatization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
not hold back on its trade liberalization and privatization
programs, which have helped revitalize the economy during the last
four years, President Fidel Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization of the country's financial and banking sectors
will continue and the privatization process will also proceed as
scheduled, a press release issued today by the Presidential Press
Office quoted Ramos as telling foreign bankers Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with foreign bankers Wednesday night, Ramos said
instead of slowing down or reversing gear on trade liberalization
and privatization, the government will deepen pro-market reforms
in order to position the country as Asia's most attractive
investment haven once the currency turmoil in the region blows
over.
</P>
<P>
"The comparative strength of the Philippine economy has
encouraged us to deepen the pro-market reforms we have
instituted," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Consistent implementation of economic reform, Ramos said, is
necessary to "make the Philippines the most attractive in
investments terms."
</P>
<P>
In view of the currency crisis striking the country in July,
the government decided to review its tariff reduction program and
planned to slow down tariff reduction for industries that are
having difficulty in competing with imports.
</P>
<P>
The United States earlier issued a strong warning against the
Philippines over a plan to slow down on the reduction of tariff
rates of imported products, saying this could "cast strong doubt
on the consistency of the Philippine policy in this area."
</P>
</TEXT>
