<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Nuclear Wasteland Attracts Explorers, Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Lop Nur, a nuclear wasteland in
northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, is becoming a
top attraction for explorers and tourists.
</P>
<P>
A prosperous history, an adverse natural environment, rich
cultural relics, unsettled academic questions, a vanishing
civilization and an ancient city on this vast wasteland all
contribute to attracting explorers and tourists.
</P>
<P>
The death of Chinese explorer Yu Chunshun, who died while
walking through the area in June of 1996, aroused concerns from
both domestic and overseas explorer and travel circles.
</P>
<P>
A year later, an explorer from Xinjiang declared that he had
successfully walked through Lop Nur on his own. In September of
this year, a Xinjiang athlete successfully crossed the wasteland
by motorcycle. In October, 100 Chinese tourists walked through Lop
Nur, often called a "zone of death."
</P>
<P>
A dozen foreign exploring teams from Japan, Britain and
Singapore have trekked the wasteland in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Lop Nur, a communications hub on the ancient Silk Roads, was a
huge lake and marshland until it dried up in 1972.
</P>
<P>
Exploration in the area dates back to the late 19th century,
when a Russian explorer visited there and captured a wild horse in
1876. Fourteen years later, the legendary Silk Roads city of
Lolan, a bustling commercial center 2,000 years ago, was
discovered by a Swedish archeologist.
</P>
<P>
Disputes in academic circles now focus on the reasons for the
disappearance of the ancient Lolan Kingdom and the drying up of
Lop Nur lake.
</P>
<P>
Several dry female corpses, known as "Lolan Beauty," have been
discovered in the area.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists He Dexiu said, "Lolan has been listed as a site
of cultural relics under state protection. There are many tombs
unearthed and numerous cultural relics such as stone tools, coins
and pieces of porcelain scattered on the earth's surface."
</P>
<P>
Another unsettled question is how people live in this region,
known as "a forbidden zone."
</P>
<P>
In 1964, a group of 100 people was found alive in the area and
evacuated to other places.
</P>
<P>
Most present-day explorers and tourists come to Lop Nur just to
experience the adverse natural environment featuring howling
winds, terrible drought and searing sunlight.
</P>
<P>
A survey of tourists' motives for visiting shows that 80
percent of them are seeking an adventurous experience.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
