<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bank Governor Urges Investors Not to Panic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Thailand Governor
Chaiyawat Wibulswasdi has urged investors not to panic over the
further decline of the baht.
</P>
<P>
He said on Wednesday that pressure on the baht stemmed from
regional concerns about the South Korean financial crisis, in
addition to strong year-end corporate dollar-buying in the Thai
market.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday the baht continued its week-long slide against the
US dollar, setting a historic low of 42.55 to the dollar onshore,
more than 63 percent down since the float of the baht five months
ago.
</P>
<P>
The baht dropped to a record low of 43.05 to the dollar in
early afternoon trading, but strengthened on the Bank of
Thailand's intervention to close at 42.55.
</P>
<P>
Offshore, the baht was quoted at 42.30 to the dollar in late
trading.
</P>
<P>
Chaiyawat predicted that the pressure would ease once
negotiations between South Korea and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) are concluded, according to the local press today.
</P>
<P>
He added that additional funds of 1 billion dollars would be
made available by the IMF to Thailand if necessary in the event
that South Korea and Indonesia have to withdraw their previous
pledge to the Thai standby credit program.
</P>
<P>
However, Olarn Chaipravat, chairman of the Thai Bankers
Association, Wednesday blamed the fall to a rush for dollars by
anxious Thai corporations facing foreign debt repayments.
</P>
<P>
He said concerns about the baht's value had pushed local
corporations to buy dollars and forward swaps to hedge against
exchange risks, which in turn put downward pressure on the value
of the baht.
</P>
<P>
Some money market analysts said the baht could weaken further,
as debt repayment by Thai companies at the end of the year would
put further downward pressure on the baht.
</P>
<P>
Some dealers agreed that the baht would hit 45 to the dollar
unless local and regional sentiment improves.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Skeleton of Early Mammal Found in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
confirmed that a prehistoric mammal, whose skeleton was unearthed
in Jianshan Valley of northeast China's Liaoning Province, lived
here as long ago as 130 million years.
</P>
<P>
The 13-centimeter-long fossilized skeleton is believed to
belong to symmetrodonta, the earliest mammal in the world. The
skeleton is so well-preserved that each part can be clearly
identified with only the tail missing.
</P>
<P>
The animal resembles a mouse, but has a sharper and longer
mouth. Experts believe that it has close kinship with the common
ancestor of both the marsupials and placentals.
</P>
<P>
The skeleton was named "Zhanghe Beast" after its donator, Zhang
He, an amateur collector, who sent the fossil to the Institute of
Vertebrate Paleontolgy and Paleoanthropolgy (IVPP) of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Hu Yaoming, 31, the major researcher on "Zhanghe Beast" in
IVPP, told Xinhua that it's the first well-preserved symmetrodonta
skeleton.
</P>
<P>
Before the recent discovery, scientists knew the existence of
such an animal only from odd fossil pieces of lower jaws or teeth.
</P>
<P>
Hu said the dating of "Zhanghe Beast" was based on two
factors: the large number of fossils of primeval birds, reptiles,
fish and invertebrates found at the same location of "Zhanghe
Beast"; and isotopic chronology tests.
</P>
<P>
Ye Jie, deputy director of IVPP, said that 130 million years
ago dinosaurs were the main animals on Earth, and mammals began
multiplying rapidly about 65 million years later.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of "Zhanghe Beast" will shed new light on the
origin of the mammal and its early evolution as research
continues, Ye said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
