<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Leader Asks Anti-Graft Officials to Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President Chandrika
Kumaratunga has asked three top anti-corruption officials to
resign in order to settle their dispute and enable the country's
anti-graft organ to work properly.
</P>
<P>
Justice and Constitutional Affairs Minister G. L. Peiris said
at a press conference this morning that Commissioner Rudra
Rajasingham, Chairman T. A. D. S. Wijesundera and Director General
Nelum Gamage of the Permanent Commission on Bribery and Corruption
have been asked to quit by the president.
</P>
<P>
Because of the dispute between the top officials, the
functioning of the commission has been very seriously impaired,
Peiris said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has a primary responsibility to ensure
that the commission is able to function properly.
</P>
<P>
That is the reason that the president has taken the step to
remove them, the minister said, adding that the matter has also
put before the parliament for discussion.
</P>
<P>
The president's intervention came at a time when a long-drawn
controversy between the commission and its director general has
developed into a crisis which has reduced the commission to a
virtual breakdown.
</P>
<P>
The commission had asked its director general to appear before
subordinate officials of the commission to explain allegations
that she had drawn holiday and risk allowances without
authorization.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, she was asked to explain the role she had played
during investigations into corruption allegations against two
suspects with whom her husband was reported to have business
relations.
</P>
<P>
In reaction, the director general filed a petition to the
Supreme Court, claiming the commission was treating her with
"malice and hostility."
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources here said a new team is to be named soon
to head the anti-graft body.  
</P>
</TEXT>
