<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Reforest Land Devastated by Fires </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia will soon reforest
land and plantations that have been burnt by fires during this
year's protracted drought, an official of the Forestry Ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
About 300,000 hectares of forest land in Indonesia were burnt
by fires during the prolonged drought this year, Director General
for Reforestation and Land Rehabilitation at the Forestry Ministry
Hendarsun said Wednesday in Palembang, South Sumatra province,
reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
The figure was based on data obtained through satellite, but
needed to be checked further, Hendarsun said.
</P>
<P>
He added that of the 300,000 hectares, 150,000 hectares were
small holders' forest land and the rest were owned by forest
concessionaires and plantation companies.
</P>
<P>
According to Hendarsun, the government is planning to replant
30,000 hectares of small holders' forests and the project is
scheduled to be completed by March 1998.
</P>
<P>
The project will be carried out in cooperation with the people
living around the devastated areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government will also help reforest 162,000 hectares of land
by providing seeds. The rest will be replanted by forest
concessionaires and plantation companies, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
