<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former UN Chief Calls for Expansion of Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Former Secretary General
of the United Nations Kurt Waldheim has called for the expansion
of the Security Council to make it more representative of world
powers.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council has to be restructured because its
composition does not reflect the present situation," said Waldheim
in an interview with the local daily Arab Times published today.
</P>
<P>
He picked Japan, Germany, Brazil and India as candidates for
the permanent members of an enlarged Security Council, according
to the daily.
</P>
<P>
Waldheim, who is currently on a private visit to Kuwait, took
the top post of the world organization in January 1972 for two,
five-year terms.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the number of the non-permanent members of
the Security Council should be increased to between 20 and 25 from
the current 15 to reflect the current political situations of the
world.
</P>
<P>
He criticized the U.N. for not performing well in recent years
and being undermined by national interests of certain "great
powers." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
