<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia to Offer 1 Billion US Dollars to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Australia today promised to
contribute 1 billion US dollars to an international back-up fund
as part of a 55 billion dollar rescue package agreed upon between
South Korea and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Australian Treasurer Peter Costello said today the contribution
would form part of a second line of defense which would be called
upon in the event that IMF, World Bank and Asian Development Bank
resources proved insufficient for South Korea to complete a
required restructuring program.
</P>
<P>
This is the third time Australia has agreed to provide aid to
an Asian country hit by the currency turmoil in the region in the
past few months, following its 1 billion dollar aid to Thailand
and a same sum to Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
But, Costello said he expected the South Korea rescue would be
the last after IMF interventions in Indonesia and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Costello said "the government's willingness to provide support
for the Republic of Korea reflects the importance it attaches to
Australia's relationship with a major trading partner and its
strong commitment to the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Costello told reporters in Canberra that he expected the IMF
intervention in South Korea would finally end the spread of the
financial contagion from Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the second major destination for Australian
exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Personal Forex Trading Active in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
economic and commercial center, witnessed active private trading
in foreign exchange during the first 10 months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the turnover for private foreign exchange
trading at the Bank of Communications for the January-October
period surged by 290 percent on the previous year's period, with
the highest daily trade volume surpassing five million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
In addition to normal over-the-counter transactions, the Bank
of Communications also offers trading via telephone and trading at
night.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai became the first Chinese city to offer private foreign
exchange trading in the second half of 1993. The Shanghai branch
of the Bank of China and the Bank of Communications were the first
financial institutions to introduce related services.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that the volume of foreign exchange
trading has increased significantly in recent months, with the
increase, at least in part, attributed to turbulence on financial
markets in Southeast Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks to Attract More Foreign Talents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China will strengthen its
efforts to attract foreign talents by offering better working and
living conditions, and by protecting their intellectual property
and other rights.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting here on foreign expert programs for 1998, Wu
Yongxing, vice director of China's State Bureau of Foreign Experts
Affairs, said the support of foreigners working in China is
important in the opening-up drive.
</P>
<P>
The bureau will seek guidance from foreigners to assist China's
reform efforts in such areas as finance, taxation, circulation
systems and internal management, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in each of the last five years 800 foreign
experts had been hired. This year 300 are from Japan and 220 from
Germany.
</P>
<P>
Expert associations in foreign countries are also playing a
bigger role in China. The German Government increased financial
support to these organizations after its favorable assessment this
fall for 17 programs in east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
China will place more importance on attracting foreign talents
to the central and western regions to promote their economic
growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> &AMP;0                      by Li Jiasheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indian government has
taken various measures to help poor and backward areas in the
country develop their economy in an effort to alleviate and
eradicate poverty.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, about one-third of the
population in India live under the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
Since India's independence in 1947, successive governments have
 regarded poverty alleviation and eradication as one of their
priorities and carried out various programs for their realization.
</P>
<P>
A main measure is the establishment of the National Backward
Classes Finance and Development Corporation, a non-profit company
to promote economic and development activities for backward
classes.
</P>
<P>
Besides, both the central and state governments have worked out
special assistance plans and programs for the purpose of poverty
alleviation.
</P>
<P>
The government has also adopted preferential policies
encouraging private and foreign investments in poor areas to help
boost agricultural and industrial production.
</P>
<P>
Various workshops and training centers were also set up at
various levels in the country to train people in poor areas on
production skills and techniques to enhance their self-employment
capacities.
</P>
<P>
The government has also provided special allowance for poor
people to buy cheaper daily necessities.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government has paid great attention to
adult education in poor areas. Every year the government and
non-governmental organizations send students and volunteers to
poor areas to help the people there learn how to read and write.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister I. K. Gujral earlier this year even suggested
that each middle-school and university student should at least
help three people overcome illiteracy before they get graduate
certificates.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Indian government has also made efforts to
enhance cooperation with other South Asian countries in
alleviating and eradicating poverty.
</P>
<P>
At the sixth summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) in Colombo, Sri Lanka, in 1991, poverty
alleviation was given the highest priority.
</P>
<P>
At the eighth SAARC summit held here in 1995, the heads of
state of member countries reaffirmed their commitment to
eradicating poverty in South Asia, preferably by the year 2002 and
declared 1995 as the "SAARC Year of Poverty Eradication."
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in 1985, embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
But for India, a big country with a population of more than 900
million, poverty alleviation and eradication remain a long-term
and very hard task that calls for political will and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
