<HEADLINE> Japan Confident in Beating China at Asian Women's Soccer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Japan, losing finalist to
China two years ago, is expecting a reversed result this time as
the 11th Asian Women's Soccer Championship kicks off here
tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Japan has set the qualifying berth to 1999 FIFA's World
Championship for women soccer as a target and the gold medal of
the tournament as a bonus, Head coach Satoshi Miyauchi said.
</P>
<P>
The top three squads of the tournament will qualify to the 3rd
World Women's Championship, which will be held in the United
States in two years' time.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to qualify and to win this Championship," he said.
</P>
<P>
And he thinks the odds that his team will topple the defending
champions China is 50 to 50.
</P>
<P>
His prediction seems well-grounded in that the Chinese girls
went through a bad patch during their visit to Japan this June,
which saw a poor record of one goaless draw and one 0-1 loss in
the two sides' most recent two encounters.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day tournament will feature 11 teams in three groups,
with the group winners and the best runners-up entering the last
four.
</P>
<P>
Japan, based in the Panyu city-- a 30 minutes' bus ride from
here, also have Hong Kong (China), India and Guam in their
group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
