<HEADLINE> Anti-kidnap Force Reinforced in Philippine Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- One thousand more policemen have
been ordered to be deployed in the Philippine capital area to
reinforce the anti-kidnapping drive there, a senior police
official said today.
</P>
<P>
Senior Superintendent Nestorio Gualberto, chief of the
country's anti-kidnapping force, said that 1,000 policemen from
Central and Southern Luzon will be sent to Metro Manila to step up
crackdown on rampant kidnapping syndicates.
</P>
<P>
Gualberto said police chief Director General Recaredo Sarmiento
had ordered an all-out campaign against kidnap-for-ransom
syndicates in the wake of a new wave of abductions of wealthy
Filipino-Chinese traders.
</P>
<P>
He said the extra policemen will be assigned to the areas where
kidnappings and probable abduction would likely occur.
</P>
<P>
Gualberto also appealed to the community to help the police in
combating kidnapping syndicates.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, thousands of Chinese-Filipinos took part in a
protest march in downtown Manila and a funeral for a young
Filipino-Chinese businessman killed by his abductors late last
month.
</P>
<P>
Chinese businesses and schools were also closed for one day
Wednesday in Chinatown and other parts of the capital city to
protest the government failure to solve the protracted kidnapping
issue.
</P>
<P>
But as the Chinese community took to the street, kidnappers
struck again in Metro Manila Tuesday, abducting five
Filipino-Chinese businessmen in separate incidents.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
