<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Seeks for Assistance in Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has asked the World
Bank for help in fighting against corruption, a senior World
Bank official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a two-day national public procurement forum in Entebbe,
Randolph Harris, the bank's representative to Uganda, said the
battle against corruption is a new mandate to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is one of the six African countries seeking for the
help from the bank. The others are Benin, Ethiopia, Malawi, Mali
and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan leaders including President Yoweri Museveni have
reaffirmed repeatedly their determination against corruption. Ali
Kirunda Kivijinja, then minister without portfolio, resigned in
June this year since Police Criminal Investigation Department has
raised a file of power abuse against him.
</P>
<P>
Harris said the World Bank has amended its procurement
guidelines so that at the request of the borrower, an
understanding to observe the country's law on bribery is
considered as part of the anti corruption
campaign.
</P>
<P>
The forum, organized by the Central Tender Board and Central
Purchasing Corporation among others, has drawn permanent
secretaries of ministries, procuring agencies, accounting
officers and heads of government and private agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
