review all aspects of the joint immigration treaties.
(Cuba-US-Immigration Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States will not make final judgments
about a Russian proposal for further cuts in its nuclear arsenal
until Moscow ratifies the START-2, State Department spokesman
James Rubin told reporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The START-2 arms reduction treaty, which provides for Russia
and the United States to reduce their long-range nuclear forces to
a maximum of 3,500 warheads each, was signed in 1993 but ratified
so far only by the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, during his visit to Sweden,
Wednesday announced plans to unilaterally cut Moscow's nuclear
warheads "by a further one-third." (US-Russia-Weapons)
</P>
<P>
