<HEADLINE> Lion Statue Rises from the Mud in Yuanmingyuan Park </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A stone lion, buried in the
bottom of Fuhai Lake in Yuanmingyuan Park for more than 100 years,
was extricated from the mud Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
More cultural relics may be buried in the lake along with the
lion statue, which is a symbol of safety in water, experts said.
</P>
<P>
A project to remove mud from the lake was launched in
November. Workers were given lessons on relic protection before
they began excavation, according to today's Beijing Youth Daily.
</P>
<P>
The cultural objects found in the lake will be managed by a
special relics protection group, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Located in Haidian District, a northwestern suburb of Beijing,
Yuanmingyuan was once the largest summer palace in China. It was
destroyed by British and French troops in 1900.
</P>
<P>
To improve the park, the district government has budgeted 17
million yuan (2.04 million U.S. dollars) on the lake reclamation
project, which covers more than 30 hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
