<HEADLINE> Zambia Takes Measures to Fight Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) --The Zambian government has taken
concrete measures against corruptive practices among government
officials that use council vehicles and offices for personal
purposes, government-owned Zambia Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The government has with immediate effect banned mayors and
council chairmen countrywide from using council vehicles and
offices for personal purposes.
</P>
<P>
Christmas and new year parties on council acounts are also
banned.
</P>
<P>
The papaer quoted Jim Katongo, the Local Governmental and
Housing Acting Permanert Secretary, as warning in a letter dated
November 30 that those defying the directive will be surcharged
or penalised.
</P>
<P>
"My office has been inundated with numerous queries from rate
payers and residents at large regarding the use of mayoral
vehicle and the office. I wish to further remind you that this
vehicle shall only be used on civic funcitons where the mayor in
his official capacity is required to be present," said Katongo.
</P>
<P>
He cited the examples to be banned such as ferrying children
and other family members for private trips and other private and
personal errands by the civic leader.
</P>
<P>
The ban follows growing abuse of council facilities in several
towns by civic leaders.
</P>
<P>
It is said that some councilors reported to work at 08:00
hours and left at 17:00 hours. During this time they use
telephones, stationery and other equipment for their personal
business.
</P>
<P>
Acting local government minister Samuel Miyanda warned earlier
that apart from privately arranged parties, no council-sponsored
Christmas parties shall be allowed this year and the same applies
to new year festivals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
