<HEADLINE> Traditional Medicine Plays Key Role in Developing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Some 80 percent of people in
developing countries have no access to modern health facilities,
and thus have to rely on traditional medicines, a leading
authority in traditional health care said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nhlavana Maseko, President of the International Traditional
Healers Organisation for Africa, was speaking at a five-day
workshop on indigenous methods of preserving natural resources
held in Masvingo, south Zimbabwe. He saud that traditional forms
of medicine play a key role even in modern times.
</P>
<P>
Justifying the use of traditional forms of healing, Maseko
said the history of traditional curative services is as old as
the history of Africa itself.
</P>
<P>
After all, he said, before the African continent was colonised
people on the continent relied on traditional medicines from its
bushes.
</P>
<P>
"The people of Africa strongly believe in traditional health
care, which is part of their culture. In the old days during the
years of our grandfathers, the modern medicines such as pills and
injections were not known," he added.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which seeks to persuade people in the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) to attach importance to
indigenous methods of improving their lives, has drawn
traditional healers, spirit mediums and war veterans from eight
SADC countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
