<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Imports Power from Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe started importing
cheap power from Mozambique on Monday when the power line linking
the two electricity grids became commercially operational, daily
newspaper The Herald reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a spokesman for the Zimbabwe Electricity
Supply Authority (ZESA) as saying that the country is now
importing 400 million units of power from Cabora Bassa Hydro
Power Station in Songo of Mozambique, through the
Songo-Bindura-Dema 420 kv inter-connector.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has become Zimbabwe's single largest source of
energy. Zimbabwe used to rely heavily on Zambia, South Africa and
Zaire (now the Democratic Republic of Congo) for power import.
</P>
<P>
Since Monday, energy imports from South African Power Utility
Eskom, have been halved to 159 mw. Imports from Zambia and the
former Zaire have been temporarily stopped and expected to resume
in cases of emergencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
