<HEADLINE> Chongqing Promotes Liquefied Natural Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The southwestern China
municipality of Chongqing is vigorously promoting the use of
liquefied natural gas for motor vehicles, with some 150 vehicles
currently using the fuel.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government plans to promote the use of liquefied
natural gas by encouraging the production of automobiles adapted
to use the fuel, and refitting motor vehicles currently using
gasoline and diesel fuel.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, 500 vehicles will be refitted by the end
of this year, with an additional 10,000 motor vehicles using the
fuel by the end of 1998, and the figure rising even further to
50,000 units by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Environmental experts note that liquefied natural gas creates
much less pollution than gasoline and diesel, with equal distance
operating costs falling by as much as 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing now has four refueling stations for liquefied natural
gas.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that Chongqing is currently faced with serious
pollution partly caused by motor vehicle emissions. They attribute
the high level of pollution to the over 200,000 vehicles operating
in the city and poor road conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
