<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Technology Breakthrough Made in Corn Yield </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A 600 sq.m. nonirrigated
experimental plot in northeast China's Jilin Province, one of the
nation's grain production bases, has yielded 1,056 kg. of corn.
</P>
<P>
Li Weiyue, a corn expert who participated in the experiment,
explained the cultivation method during a recent seminar on high
yield corn technology. Li noted that the test plot is located
close to a rice field.
</P>
<P>
He said the technology will make it possible to increase the
per unit corn production in the northeastern plains, which
produces a major portion of China's marketable grain, by between
30-100 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shen Maoxiang, an official with the State Science and
Technology Commission, said the successful experiment will add
impetus to the important role science will play in the region's
grain production.
</P>
<P>
Jilin is home to 10.4 percent of China's corn production area,
and produces 14.8 percent of total output. However, due to the low
productivity on some four million hectares. The province's per
hectare corn yield averages a mere 6,000 kilograms.
</P>
<P>
The central government attaches great importance to the
research Jilin has carried out to increase corn production.
Related research has been integrated with the nation's
key technological projects during the Ninth Five-Year Plan Period.
</P>
<P>
Scientific agriculture introduced over the past two years has
increased corn output on 2.6 million ha by 400 million kilograms.
</P>
<P>
China plans to increase grain production by 50 billion kg, with
Jilin expected to produce 10 percent of the total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Anticipates Favorable Foreign Trade Balance in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China's foreign trade turnover
for 1998 is expected to rise by 12.5 percent to 365 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Projections call for exports to grow by 10 percent to 196
billion US dollars worth, with the import volume rising by 15
percent to 169 billion US dollars. Factors which will contribute
to the growth include reductions in import tariffs and increasing
investment demand, according to a report released by an economic
research institute under the State Planning Commission.
</P>
<P>
However, the foreign trade surplus for 1998 will drop to 27
billion US dollars, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Growth for exports of general items is expected to slow
somewhat on this year's high growth rate, while growth in imports
will rebound due to policy incentives and the rising scale of
investments.
</P>
<P>
Figures for the processing trade are expected to remain at last
year's levels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
