<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: No Judgment Until Duma Ratifies START-2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States will not
make final judgments about a Russian proposal for further cuts in
its nuclear arsenal until Moscow ratifies the START-2, State
Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters today.
</P>
<P>
The START-2 arms reduction treaty, which provides for Russia
and the United States to reduce their long-range nuclear forces to
a maximum of 3,500 warheads each, was signed in 1993 but ratified
so far only by the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
Russian President Boris Yeltsin, during his visit to Sweden,
today announced plans to unilaterally cut Moscow's nuclear
warheads "by a further one-third."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said: "It appears that President Yeltsin was stating
publicly what we have previously been told privately, that is his
willingness to consider reductions in strategic nuclear forces
below the START-3 levels agreed to at Helsinki -- that is, below
the 2,000 to 2,500 strategic nuclear warheads for each of the
parties."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott and Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Georgy Mamedov met
today and expected to discuss the subject.
</P>
<P>
The two, who meet regularly, were also expected to discuss
U.S. concerns about Russian cooperation with Iran on matters such
as missiles.
</P>
<P>
Washington insists formal negotiations cannot start until
Russia's State Duma (parliament) ratifies START-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
