<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Export Earnings Grow in July-October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's earnings from
exports reached 77.55 billion taka (45.45 taka to 1 U.S. dollar)
in the July-October period of the current fiscal year (starting
from July 1), growing by more than 21 percent over the
corresponding period of the previous fiscal year, according to
sources in the Export Promotion Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The receipts surpassed the target of 75 billion taka by about
2.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
The increase of export earnings was attributed to the increase
of Bangladeshi products' prices in the international market by
10.29 percent and to that of the export volume by 10.87 percent
over the corresponding period of the previous fiscal year, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
However, the sources said that jute goods and finished leather
were behind targets. Jute goods fetched 4.44 billion taka against
the projection of 4.52 billion taka while finished leather earned
2.57 billion taka against the target of 3.02 billion taka.
</P>
<P>
Despite the European Union's fish ban, Bangladesh still fetched
6.51 billion taka against the July-October target of 4.42 billion
taka, increasing by 10.55 percent.
</P>
<P>
Ready-made garment industry, the major foreign exchange earner
of the country, surpassed its target by about 5.85 billion taka or
39.10 percent, to reach 42.32 billion taka.
</P>
<P>
Hosiery products, however, fell short of their targets by 2.4
billion taka.
</P>
<P>
The United States topped the list of importers buying
Bangladesh products worth about 29.53 billion taka, followed by
Germany with 7.61 billion taka and the United Kingdom with 7.16
billion taka, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
