<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Legislators Reportedly Claim Big Wealth Gap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Deputies at Vietnam's National
Assembly have reportedly claimed that the gap is widening between
the country's rich and poor due to inadequate government policies.
</P>
<P>
Deputies told the on-going assembly session that the disparity
was growing in the countryside itself and between rural and urban
areas, the latest issue of Vietnamese Investment Review reported.
</P>
<P>
In the country's rural areas, they were quoted as saying,
farmers were quitting the land for cities because of falling
profits, and more incentives were needed to stop the drain.
</P>
<P>
While agricultural inputs, such as electricity, fertilizer and
irrigation services, are high priced, the output, like rice, is
often sold at low prices, one of the deputies noted.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people don't have jobs at all, simply because they
don't want an agricultural job with humble earnings."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Nguyen Cong Tan, who is in charge of
agricultural and rural development, confirmed some of these
complaints in an interview with Vietnamese Investment Review.
</P>
<P>
"Some groups in the countryside are struggling below the
poverty line without basic living conditions," the official said.
</P>
<P>
In response, he said, the government has planned to invest a
considerable amount in rural and agricultural production in a bid
to "make their living easier." 
</P>
</TEXT>
