<HEADLINE> 67 Sri Lankan Police Officers to Lose Civic Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Sixty-seven Sri Lankan police
officers charged with malpractice in the 1994 elections will be
deprived of their civic rights for seven years, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Special Presidential Commission, which has been probing the
malpractice in the general elections in August 1994 and local
elections in Eastern Province and Vavuniya, Northern Province, in
March 1994, recommended the suspension of civic rights for the
officers.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the commission recommended that the officers,
including some senior ones, be deprived of the right to vote for
seven years and imprisoned in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
The police officers were charged with trying to influence
voters, either directly or indirectly, during the elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the commission recommended that tough action be
taken against Risvy Sinna Lebbe and Kathankudi Nallaratnam
Sivaerasa, former organizers of the United National Party (UNP)
for their roles in the election malpractice.
</P>
<P>
High Court Judge G. M. S. Samaraweera said he had strong
evidence that they were involved in malpractice with the help of
police officers on March 1, 1994, the day the local government
elections were held.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports quoted the commission as saying, "Attempts
had been made to win the election through police power rather than
through the power of the ballot."
</P>
<P>
The commission, set up by the People's Alliance government
which won the 1994 general elections, also noted that voters had
no opportunity to exercise their voting rights due to the lack of
a peaceful atmosphere devoid of outside influence in the 1994
elections.
</P>
<P>
It went on to say that even some public servants had no
opportunity to fulfill their duties because of various pressures
exerted on them during the election.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
