<BODY>
<HEADLINE> San Francisco Hits Red Light Runners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 3 (Xinhua) -- San Francisco has decided
to expand its traffic high-tech surveillance program by installing
more "scofflaw" cameras at intersections.
</P>
<P>
Of the city's estimated 1,000 signalized intersections, five
are now controlled by red-light cameras. The Parking and Traffic
Commission on Tuesday agreed to bring the number of such
intersections to 30.
</P>
<P>
Each of the cameras costs 50,000 U.S. dollars and it is
expected that the expansion cost of one million dollars could be
covered by red-light fines.
</P>
<P>
The cameras will not operate all the time at each
intersection. Instead, 20 will be rotated among the 30 locations,
but drivers will never know which intersections are being watched.
</P>
<P>
Red-light running is an old and serious problem in San
Francisco. During the past five year, nearly 4,000 accidents were
caused by red-light runners, resulting in 21 deaths and 6,620
injuries.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Parking and Traffic estimates more than 3.5
million red-light violations happen each year in the city. In
1996, more than 15,000 tickets were issued for the offense.
</P>
<P>
Department officials said that since the cameras went into
operation, the number of red-light runners at these intersections
has dropped, in some months by about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Starting from January 1, the fine for going through red lights
will more than double, to 271 dollars, under a new state law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the city has begun to crack down on missing
license-plate violations, and is considering fining registered
owners of the vehicles when the drivers cannot be determined.
</P>
<P>
San Francisco, with a population of 730,000, has 428,000
registered cars, trucks and motorcycles. On average one household
has one car, and 60,000 households have two cars apiece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Private Sector Urged to Develop Maritime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad today urged the private sector to look into
technological innovations to make the maritime industry less
labor-intensive in turning the country into a true maritime
nation.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir made the appeal when opening the First International
Maritime Conference in Langkawi, some 500 kilometers north of
here, which is being held in conjunction with the ongoing six-day
Langkawi International Maritime and Aerospace (LIMA) '97 Show
which entered its third day today, the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said that although Malaysia has all the makings of a
maritime nation, being strategically located at the center of
shipping land and with a large sea area rich in fishery, oil and
gas resources, it has yet to optimize all these attributes to
qualify as a maritime nation in the true sense of the word.
</P>
<P>
He said efforts to transform Malaysia into a true maritime
nation began about two decades ago and since then the industry has
been recognized as an increasingly important sector in the
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
But the growth in the maritime industry has implied tremendous
pressure on the limited human resources in the industry, he said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the private sector to look into the possibility of
incorporating more information technology(IT) and automation in
the industry in line with Malaysia's Multimedia Super Corridor
project.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir noted that the number and capacity of local shipyards
have also increased manifold to cope with a rising level of
activities.
</P>
<P>
He said it is hoped that the Malaysian Navy would play a more
significant role in initiating warship design, building and
repairs.
</P>
<P>
His government is trying to revive the nation's seafaring
culture by inculcating maritime values among schoolchildren
through extracurricular activities like sea cadet corps.  
</P>
</TEXT>
