<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Only 3 Suspended Thai Finance Firms to Reopen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Only three of the 58 finance
companies suspended earlier this year by the Thai government are
likely to pass scrutiny and be allowed to reopen, it was learned
here today.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanhaeminda will announce on Monday
which of the suspended finance firms can reopen and how the assets
of the closed firms will be managed.
</P>
<P>
The fate of the suspended finance firms has caused much concern
in recent months in the financial sector and has been one of the
factors leading to the continued decline of the Stock Exchange of
Thailand index and the country's currency, the baht.
</P>
<P>
The 58 firms were temporarily closed down by the government in
June and August respectively because of their huge amounts of bad
and non-performing debts and mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
The government has asked them to merge, increase capital or be
taken over by other financial firms. Failing to do so will lead to
their close-down.
</P>
<P>
Estimates of the good assets held by the suspended firms run
from 400 billion to 500 billion baht (10 billion to 12.5 billion
U.S. dollars), the size of a medium-sized bank with 1,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
The bad assets of the 55 firms expected to be closed will be
sold to the state-supported Asset Management Corporation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
