<HEADLINE> Postal Workers Back to Work in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Postal workers in Canada today
announced their decision to return to workplace Thursday after two
weeks of walkout.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the government passed a tough legislation
through the federal parliament to force the Canadian Union of
Postal Workers (CUPW) back to work.
</P>
<P>
But mail would be processed without stamps and corporate mail
could be sent to wrong addresses, the union warned.
</P>
<P>
Postal workers are to face fines of up to 1,000 Canadian
dollars (730 U.S. dollars) a day, union leaders 50,000 dollars
(36,500 U.S. dollars) and the union 100,000 dollars (73,000
U.S. dollars) if they defy the legislation.
</P>
<P>
However, the workers vowed to continue their fight against
Canada Post, a Crown corporation in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We will return to work by taking our struggle into the
workplace," CUPW President Darrel Tingley said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
