<HEADLINE> Media Giants Urged To End Dispute Over Pay TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The world soccer governing body
FIFA on Wednesday told the television rights holders to the 2002
and 2006 World Cups that they are expected to reaffirm their total
acceptance of FIFA's demands for optimum TV coverage in Europe and
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
FIFA made this notice at Marseille on the eve of the World Cup
draw ceremony.
</P>
<P>
FIFA has worldwide television deals wrapped up totalling 930
million U.S. dollars in 2002 to rise to 1.15 billion U.S. dollars
in 2006 with the companies Sporis/ISL and the German media giant
Kirch/Taurus.
</P>
<P>
But there are fears that the costly subscription service could
cost the wide fan base a chance to see their teams live.
</P>
<P>
FIFA last year ruled out pay-per-view from any distribution
policy, stressing pay TV options would have to be limited as much
as possible and would be assessed on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
Plans were undergoing consideration last month that would
guarantee free live transmission of 2002 World Cup in South Korea
and Japan to only four of the 64 games.
</P>
<P>
Most games during the next year's World Cup in France will
still be broadcast on traditional over-the-air public and
commercial networks, free of charge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
