<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Proposes Changes in Boeing 747s </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The United States Federal
Aviation Administration (FAA) today proposed changes in Boeing
747s to reduce the possibility of fuel tank explosions, a
suspected reason for the Trans World Airline (TWA) plane crash
last year.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was made following recommendations by the National
Transportation Safety Board that new, and possibly older, Boeing
747 aircraft be fitted with nitrogen inert systems in fuel tanks
and that insulation be added between heat-generating equipment and
fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
Investigators suspected that an electrical surge may have
ignited an explosion in the center fuel tank of the TWA plane.
</P>
<P>
The plane exploded on July 17, 1996, killing all 230 people on
board.
</P>
<P>
The safety board is convening a week-long hearing in Baltimore
next week to further investigate the cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, the FAA urged airlines to install new equipment
over the next 12 months to shield certain wiring in the fuel
monitoring system in some Boeing 747s, and to inspect wiring in
some fuel pumps in older 747s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
