<HEADLINE> Myanmar Ministries Urged to Cooperate in Drug Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar leader Khin Nyunt has
called for cooperation among government ministries and between
Myanmar and international organizations in fighting against
narcotic drug abuse.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a special meeting here Wednesday of the Myanmar
Central Committee for Drug Abuse Control, Khin Nyunt, first
secretary of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, also
urged effective implementation of the country's narcotic drug
control program, the official newspaper The New Light of Myanmar
reported today.
</P>
<P>
"Since 1989 when the armed groups began returning to the legal
fold, consultations have been conducted with national race leaders
to achieve understanding on eradicating narcotic drugs and
implement regional development projects, to carry out two programs
in combination," he said.
</P>
<P>
He cited two of the Myanmar government's accomplishments, the
surrender of more than 10,000 members of the Mong Tai Army led by
former drug warlord Khun Sa and the abandonment of its narcotic
drug production and trafficking in January 1996, and the
declaration of the Mongla region in the country's eastern Shan
State as an area totally free from narcotic drugs in April 1997.
</P>
<P>
The meeting discussed cooperation among various ministries for
the cultivation of opium-substitute crops, cooperation with
international organizations and formulation of a program to
mobilize non-governmental organizations to participate in the
project to totally eradicate narcotic drugs in Myanmar, the report
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Rupiah Hits New Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian rupiah hit a new
record low Wednesday due to regional weaknesses as stocks
continued to fall, dealers and stockbrokers here said today.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah touched a new historical low of 3,980 against the
U.S. dollar in the spot market Wednesday before easing to 3,930/50
at the close in Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Currency dealers said the rupiah ended at 3,985 in Singapore
and 3,920/45 in London.
</P>
<P>
The central bank was not seen intervening in the spot market,
but it sold dollars and drained the rupiah from the swap and money
markets, a local bank chief dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the rupiah was under heavy trade Wednesday after
Indonesian Finance Minister Mar'ie Muhammad said joint
intervention with Singapore and Japan to support the rupiah was
temporarily suspended.
</P>
<P>
Some economists said the government should be realistic that
the current crisis is driven by huge private offshore debts which
had reached 65 billion dollars as of September this year and
therefore it should help the private sector settle those debts.
</P>
<P>
They said indebted local corporations have been looking for
dollars in the market, fearing that the rupiah would continue to
drop to an unseen bottom as it is not guarded by the central bank.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has fallen steadily since July, with a brief spell
of stabilization in early November after the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) provided a financial bailout package to
Indonesia to bring relief to its economy.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, the value of the rupiah has
dropped by near 50 percent against the U.S. dollar this year. The
IMF agreed at the end of October to provide 23 billion dollars in
long-term financial aid to Indonesia to help it overcome its
monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Jakarta Stock Exchange composite index was down
1.2 percent or 4.6 points to close at 389.68 Wednesday, with a
total turnover of 77.81 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brokers blamed the decline in stock prices on the weakening
rupiah, negative corporate earnings and the upcoming year-end
holiday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Inflation Increases In First 11 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's cumulative
inflation rate from January through November 1997 reached 9.01
percent, higher than a year earlier when it stood at 5.92 percent,
according to data issued by the Central Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate in November was recorded at 1.65 percent, up
by 1.08 percentage points from the 0.57 percent in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The cumulative inflation rate for the first eight months of
fiscal year 1997/98 (April 1-March 31) stood at 7.05 percent, also
higher than the 2.66 percent in fiscal 1996/97.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the November inflation rate was the result of a
rise in the index of food, housing and various goods and services,
the statistics bureau said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, chief of the statistics bureau Sugito warned that the
country's inflation rate could break the double-digit barrier this
year if the government does not take extra measures to facilitate
the supply of goods and services.
</P>
<P>
He said month-on-month inflation rates have been going up
especially after the outbreak of the currency crisis last July.
</P>
<P>
The monetary crisis has caused the Indonesian rupiah to fall by
about 50 percent this year while the prices of many goods have
soared by 20 to 50 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Considers Loans to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada said today it is prepared
to provide a one billion U.S. dollars loan to South Korea as part
of an international bail-out.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has agreed to provide a
bailout of 55 billion dollars to South Korea, the latest victim in
Asia's financial turmoil which started in July.
</P>
<P>
The deal consists of 35 billion dollars from the IMF, the World
Bank and the Asia Development Bank, and 20 billion dollars from
the G-7 countries.
</P>
<P>
The first batch of 35 billion dollars is being provided
immediately.
</P>
<P>
The pledge for additional loans if needed is "intended to
demonstrate to markets that the international community is
confident that South Korea will recover," according to Canada's
Department of Finance.
</P>
<P>
South Korea is the third Asian economy after Thailand and
Indonesia that has sought IMF bail-outs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
