<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food, Clothing Inadequacy to End in Three Years (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The free aid is designated for projects such as roads,
irrigation, drinking water and telecommunications. The loans are
for growing cash crops, raising profitable animals and poultry,
improving the processing industry and developing natural resources.
</P>
<P>
"About half of the projects with loans can return the loans on
time over the years," Yang said. "The reasons are either the
people in the poor regions are unwilling to pay or the projects
don't generate money.
</P>
<P>
"For those who can't pay back loans, we show generosity and
allow them to postpone the date of repayment."
</P>
<P>
Poor people don't just reside in rural areas. Statistics from
the labor and civil affairs ministries show that 5.3 million
people are registered as unemployed and more than 12 million
people suffer from inadequate food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
For people in urban areas, China offers assistance in the form
of money and materials, vocational training and developing the
service industry.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the official sources, many non-governmental
agencies are helping to alleviate poverty.
</P>
<P>
The Foundation for Underdeveloped Regions in China is gathering
funds to tackle water shortages in northwestern China and a
shortage of farmland in southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Communist Youth League's "Hope Project" is aimed at
helping poor young people to obtain a basic education. The
All-China Women's Federation also has projects to help poor
mothers and poor girls.
</P>
<P>
More overseas companies are also joining in the battle against
poverty, Yang said.
</P>
<P>
The official stressed that solving food and clothing needs
doesn't mean shedding poverty, saying that many people take for
granted that having enough food and clothing means getting rid of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
"After tackling their food and clothing problems, China will
continue to lend them forceful support in education and medical
care," Yang said. "Poverty alleviation is a long-term goal for
China." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food, Clothing Inadequacy to End in Three Years (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- China's 58 million people who
still suffer hunger and inadequate clothing should receive needed
assistance within three years because of government support, said
a senior Chinese official here today.
</P>
<P>
"China is sure to basically solve the food and clothing problem
by the end of the century, provided that the current systematic
policies and measures remain intact in the area of poverty
alleviation," said Yang Yongyi, deputy director of the State
Council Leading Group for Poverty Alleviation and Development, in
an exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
China's poverty fight developed quickly after China adopted its
policy of reform and opening to the outside world in 1978, when
the country had 250 million people who "had not enough food in
their stomach and not enough to cover their bodies," Yang said.
</P>
<P>
During 1978-1985, China abolished communes and implemented a
policy to allow individual households to contract out farmland,
which greatly improved grain production. The state raised the
purchase price of grain, which also improved farmers'
income. Later, the State Council started to draft a series of
preferential policies to help the economy of poor regions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the official said, China annually allocates huge
amounts of money to support the poor regions, which are mainly in
northwestern and southwestern China.
</P>
<P>
The State Council's budget on poverty relief for this year was
15.3 billion yuan, with 6.5 billion yuan in free aid. The rest of
the money was offered as loans with an interest rate slightly more
than two percent a year, a rate below the corresponding inflation
rate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
