<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three million American Adults on Probation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- More than half of all adult
offenders serving criminal sentences in the United States were on
probation by the end of 1996, says a Justice Department report
released today.
</P>
<P>
State and local probation agencies were supervising about three
million adults on December 31, 1996, -- about 1.6 percent of the
U.S. adult population, or one in every 62 persons over the age of
18.
</P>
<P>
Probation is a conditional release into the community under
supervision, in lieu of incarceration.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of 1995, more than 453,000 adults were on
probation for violent offenses, 757,000 for a property offenses,
561,000 for a drug offenses and 815,000 for disturbing public
order, such as driving while intoxicated, traffic offenses,
drunkenness or morals offenses, said the survey.
</P>
<P>
The most common offenses among felons given probationary
sentences for misdemeanors were drug trafficking, 15 percent,
possession of drugs, 13 percent, drunken driving, 35 percent, and
assault, 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey results were compiled from a sample of 5,867
administrative records, the bureau said.
</P>
<P>
About 30 percent of all probationers had previously been
sentenced to jail for earlier offenses. Forty-two percent had
previously been sentenced to probation.
</P>
<P>
At the time of the survey, about 18 percent of all adult
probationers had attended one or more formal disciplinary hearings
for violating the terms of their release, the study said.
</P>
<P>
The most common violation was failure to maintain contact with
probation officers.
</P>
<P>
Since going on probation, more than 60 percent had participated
in some type of special supervision or treatment program, the
Justice Department said. About 37 percent had been in alcohol or
drug treatment programs, and 12 percent underwent special
counseling, including psychological or family counseling, or
classes in life skills or parenting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
