<HEADLINE> Green Passage in "Sea of Death" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region plans to build a green passage in Taklimakan
Desert in five years.
</P>
<P>
The desert, called "sea of death", is the second largest of its
kind in the world with an area of 330,000 sq km and sits in the
Tarim Basin in the southern part of Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, a 522-km-long road was built to cross the desert from
the north to the south, which not only facilitates oil exploration
in the region but shortens the distance from Urumqi, capital of
the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, to cities and towns at the
south edge of the basin.
</P>
<P>
Some parts of the road, however, have been damaged by shifting
sand, the local government has to spend a lot of money on
maintaining it.
</P>
<P>
Some experts concluded through prospecting that there are rich
deposits of underground water in the area. The local government,
therefore, plans to plant grass and trees on the both sides of the
road to make it "green" to ensure its transport capacity.
</P>
<P>
The concrete measures they take include building six windbreaks
by planting diversiform-leaved poplar in the 50-meter area on the
both sides of the road in five years.
</P>
<P>
The green passage, upon completion, is expected to protect the
road in desert against shifting sand in about 100 year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
