<HEADLINE> Shanghai Ranks First in Per Capita Income in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- A recent survey found that per
capita income in Shanghai for the month of October was 704 yuan,
70 percent more than the national level.
</P>
<P>
The survey covered China's 30 provinces, municipalities, and
autonomous regions, with the exception of Tibet, and found that
per capita incomes for October were 654 yuan in Beijing, 641 yuan
in Guangzhou, and 563 yuan in Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
It also showed that salaries in Shanghai only account for 53
percent of households' total earnings. Sources of income include
work for overseas-backed enterprises and money earned on the side
by retired workers.
</P>
<P>
And, while the people of Shanghai earn more than their Beijing
counterparts, their monthly expenditures are less, at 579.84 yuan
in Shanghai, against 587.94 yuan in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai residents spend 7.8 percentage points less than people
in Beijing, 4.1 percentage points less than Tianjin, and 2.9
percentage points less than Chongqing, the other three
municipalities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
