<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy Seen to Grow Modestly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine economy, as
measured by the gross national product (GNP), will reach the
low-end of this year's growth target range of 5.5 percent, the
local newspaper The Manila Chronicle said today.
</P>
<P>
Originally, the government expected a GNP growth of between 7
and 7.5 percent for 1997. But the target was brought down to
between 6 to 5.5 percent after the de facto devaluation of the
Philippine peso in July.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted sources at the inter-agency Development Budget
Coordination Committee (DBCC) as saying the GNP is expected to
slow down to about 5.5 percent for the whole of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The DBCC, tasked to map out the country's macroeconomic
targets, is composed of the Department of Finance, the Central
Bank, the National Economic and Development Authority and some
other agencies.
</P>
<P>
The DBCC attributed the slowdown in the economy to a slump in
the manufacturing sector in the third quarter of 1997 caused by
rising interest rates and the weakening local currency.
</P>
<P>
But sources at the DBCC said the target of a 6- to 6.5-percent
inflation rate would be attainable in 1997.
</P>
<P>
With the high interest rate regime and the continuing peso
depreciation, DBCC sources also admitted that "it is really
impossible to meet the 13 billion pesos (382 million U.S. dollars)
targeted budget surplus of the government."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Building Industry Developing Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The building industry in
Shanghai has developed rapidly this year because of reforms in
state-owned construction enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that the city's industrial output in the
first nine months was 33.3 billion yuan (4.16 billion
U.S. dollars), a 26 percent increase over the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
State-owned building enterprises have exceeded 23.3 billion
yuan (2.9 billion U.S. dollars) of industrial output in the first
nine months, accounting for 70 percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the state-owned building enterprises are
playing the most important role in the city's building industry.
</P>
<P>
For the period, the city's building industry has reaped 405.78
million yuan (50.72 million U.S. dollars) in profit, 29.2 percent
more than the corresponding period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned building enterprises grossed 247 million yuan
(30 million U.S. dollars), an increase of 55.6 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
