<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Threatens To Axe Los Angeles Drug Lab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) said on Wednesday the laboratory at the University
of California Los Angeles (UCLA) was on the verge of losing its
IOC accreditation for lack of state-of-art equipments to find out
drugtakers.
</P>
<P>
IOC medical chief Prince Alexandre de Merode said UCLA was the
only one of 25 IOC-accredited labs which did not have mass
spectrometers, used to detect the presence of banned substances in
an athlete's urine.
</P>
<P>
De Merode added that the IOC would consider extending the lab's
accreditation for three months if it could made sure the equipment
would be in place soon.
</P>
<P>
Besides UCLA, another IOC lab in the U.S. is in
Indianapolis.which also conducted tests on athletes from outside
the United States, said De Merode..
</P>
<P>
The testing in 1996 Atlanta Olympics has gone far from smoothly
and some positive tests had to be ignored because of technical
problems.
</P>
<P>
Since the Games, American athletics officials have been under
fire for dragging their feet over positive drugs tests involving
American 400 meters hurdler Sandra Farmer-Patrick and veteran
distance runner Mary Slaney. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
