<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baby-Friendly Action Expanding in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- Newborn babies in China now
receive better health care both at home and in hospitals due to
the rapid expansion of baby-friendly action, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health approved 1,160 more maternal and
children health centers and medical units with obstetric and
pediatric departments to be baby-friendly hospitals, raising the
number of baby-friendly hospitals in China to 5,890.
</P>
<P>
To date, about 80 percent of the country's maternal and
children health centers and hospitals at and above the county
level are baby-friendly, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Six cities, including Beijing, Shanghai, Shenzhen and Zhongshan
of Guangdong Province, and Fuzhou and Xiamen of Fujian Province,
have been recognized by the United Nations Children' Fund and the
World Health Organization as baby-friendly cities.
</P>
<P>
China launched the Baby-Friendly Initiative in response to a
call from fund and WHO in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In such hospitals, the infants are given to their mothers to
breast-feed immediately after birth. Doctors and nurses teach
mothers about breast feeding and baby care.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey in eight provinces showed that about 91 percent
of the infants are now breast-fed in hospitals, and the
breast-feeding rate has come up to 85.8 percent among babies four
months old and below.
</P>
<P>
Baby-friendly action has also expanded to the vast rural areas,
which is vital in achieving the national goal of reducing maternal
death rate by half and cutting the death rate of children below
five years old by one-third before the turn of the century,
according to the Ministry of Health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
