<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Care of Infants Improving in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 4 (Xinhua) -- More and more newborn babies in
China now receive better care both at home and in hospitals thanks
to the rapid expansion of baby-friendly action in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Health approved 1,160 more maternal and
children health centers and medical units to be baby-friendly
hospitals, raising the number of baby-friendly hospitals in China
to 5,890, today's "China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) and the world
Health Organization (WHO) recognized yesterday in Beijing six
Chinese cities as baby-friendly cities for their promotion of
baby-centered activities.
</P>
<P>
The six cities are Beijing, Shanghai, Shenzhen and Zhongshan of
Guangdong Province, and Fuzhou and Xiamen of Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
China launched the Baby-Friendly Hospital Initiative in
response to a call from UNICEF and WHO in 1992.
</P>
<P>
In such hospitals, the infants are given to their mothers to
breast-feed immediately after birth. Doctors and nurses teach
mothers about breast feeding and baby care.
</P>
<P>
A sample survey in eight provinces showed that 91 percent of
infants are now breast-fed in hospitals, and the breast-feeding
rate has come up to 85.8 percent among the babies four months old
and below.
</P>
<P>
Peng Yu, vice-minister of Health, said that the country will
continue to spread baby-friendly action to more areas in the
country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0287 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Controlling Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The city of Shanghai has had
success in preventing its environmental conditions from worsening,
according to Shen Yonglin of the Environmental Protection Bureau,
by controlling the discharge of major industrial pollutants and
reducing air pollution during a period of fast economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In the next two years, the city will spend three percent of its
GDP annually on environmental protection, compared with two
percent in the 1993-95 period and 2.34 percent in 1996, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
A sewage diversion project costing six billion yuan (722
million US dollars) and a 2.6-billion-yuan project for improving
the quality of drinking water are being built.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai has spent six billion yuan on pollution-reduction
efforts that involved moving 850 factories and workshops causing
serious pollution out of downtown areas in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
However, as an old industrial center, Shanghai has many
pollution problems that have existed since last century, Shen
said, and the situation could get worse if steps are not taken
immediately, because the city is undergoing massive construction
and its economy is growing faster than ever before.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
