<HEADLINE> IOC Warnes Osaka Officials Against 2008 Lobbying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 4 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee (IOC) on Wednesday warned Osaka, the only declared
candidate so far for the 2008 Summer Olympics, against launching a
publicity campaign during the Winter Games in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
Osaka officials planned an outlay of 500,000 U.S. dollars and
rented three buildings in Nagano to promote their bid during the
February 7-22 games.
</P>
<P>
But the IOC sent a letter to the Japanese Olympic Committee
stressing that Nagano is not the time and place to lobby its bid
for the 2008 games, said IOC director general Francois Carrard.
</P>
<P>
The director general added that although IOC was particularly
intent on keeping Osaka representatives away from IOC meetings and
functions in Nagano, IOC could yet not ban Osaka officials from
going to Nagano or carrying out activities at non-Olymic sites.
</P>
<P>
IOC will decide the final winner of the bid for the 2008 games
in 2001. 
</P>
