<HEADLINE> Canada, Norway Sign Trade Arrangement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada and Norway signed an
arrangement on trade and economic cooperation here today.
</P>
<P>
The arrangement will further boost economic relations between
the two countries and encourage alliances between Canadian and
Norwegian companies, according to a government news release.
</P>
<P>
It "should strengthen our collaboration in multilateral forums,
and bilaterally, will be of mutual benefit," said Canadian
International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi.
</P>
<P>
"Through this arrangement, we will identify and analyze our
trade and investment flows with a view to enhancing the bilateral
trade and investment relationship," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will try to "create the most favorable
conditions" for liberalization of trade in goods and services and
investment, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Trade ties between the two countries have improved much over
the last three years. In 1996, Canada-Norway trade exceeded 3.6
billion dollars (2.5 billion U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
Canada's imports from Norway were mainly petroleum products,
while its exports consist mostly of base metal and minerals,
aircraft and telecommunications equipment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
