<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Falls Against Mark But Higher Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar edged higher
against Japanese yen but fell against the mark on strong German
economic data and a warning from a German central bank official
about higher interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In late New York trading, the dollar settled at 1.7720 marks,
down from 1.7782 Tuesday. The dollar also was changing hands at
128.78 yen, up from 128.64.
</P>
<P>
The mark rallied against the dollar and yen after the release of
German industrial output figures that showed a 1.8 percent rise in
October, surpassing analysts' projections for a 1.3 percent rise.
</P>
<P>
Against the yen, the dollar rose to a high of 128.98 yen before
retreating on worries about lifting the dollar too high and
causing Japanese officials to intervene and support the yen.
</P>
<P>
The British pound was quoted at 1.6829 U.S. dollars, up from
1.6807 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Tuesday:
1.4301 Swiss francs, down from 1.4335; 5.9315 French francs, down
from 5.9490; 1,736 Italian lire, down from 1,740; and 1.4191
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4195. 
</P>
</TEXT>
