<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Faces Tough Test in Bonn: Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu will face a tough test when he comes to Bonn to meet
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on Thursday evening, German press
reports quoted diplomatic sources as saying today.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu had to convince Kohl that he was planning to take
concrete steps towards peace, otherwise he would risk an attitude
change in Germany's Middle East policy, the German news agency DPA
quoted western diplomats as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kohl wanted to give Netanyahu one last chance to prove himself
before deciding whether Germany would drop its traditional support
of Israel's policies and take a more neutral line in the Middle
East conflict, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the talks with Kohl, Netanyahu is also due to meet
U.S. Secretary of State Madeline Albright and French President
Jacques Chirac on Friday and Saturday in a bid to enlist their
support for his plans for a limited withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet agreed in principle on Sunday to partly
withdraw troops from the West Bank, but it set no date and
attached a string of hardline demands on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israeli media reported today that the Israeli government was
planning a conditional handover of some eight percent of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have rejected the Israeli proposal as
insufficient, and says that it is ploy to keep the territory under
its control. 
</P>
</TEXT>
