<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Struggle Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 3 (Xinhua) -- New York stocks managed to
turn around today after slipping for the second straight session
amid worries about the profits of technology companies.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 13.18 points to 8,032.01,
after erasing an early 57-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
Advancers outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-7 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 623.44 million shares,
up from 575.29 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list rose 5.09 to 976.77, less
than 7 points from its October 7 record finish at 983.12.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 2.50 to 510.14, about 4 points
shy of record terrain.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index, which fell as much as 15 points
during the session, rose 8.76 to 1,615.13 at the end.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.32 to
433.80, and the small-company dominated American Stock Exchange
composite index rose 3.40 to 669.10.
</P>
<P>
Helping cushion the decline in stocks was a strong day in the
bond market, where the key yield on the 30-year Treasury nearly
grazed 6 percent for the first time since early 1996. The yield
fell as low as 6.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
In another sign that economic growth may be easing enough to
keep inflation low, the Commerce Department reported that sales of
new homes slipped 1.7 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
