<HEADLINE> IDB Assists Mexico's Education, Financial Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) today announced the approval of two loans
to Mexico for a total of 179 million U.S. dollars equivalent to
help upgrade education and financial supervision.
</P>
<P>
A loan of 171 million dollars will provide resources for a
program to improve middle school education in remote rural areas.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the program, it will use educational
television to broaden and improve the quality of instruction for
both youth and adults in grades seven through nine in communities
that were previously denied access to instruction because of
isolation and lack of resources.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is some 285.8 million dollars.
Apart from the IDB loan which is for a 20-year term, local
counterpart funds total 114.8 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another loan of 8 million dollars will assist the Mexican
Banking and Security Commission in its capacity as supervisor of
capital markets and banking institutions, with the goal of
enhancing the soundness and stability of the financial system. The
total cost of the program is 16 million dollars. Local counterpart
funds total 8 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
