<HEADLINE> Clinton Holds Forum on Race in Ohio </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
hosted the first public forum on race relations in the country in
Akron, Ohio on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president moderated a 90-minute discussion on race
relations with about 65 students and community leaders
</P>
<P>
Clinton, linked from the University of Akron via satellite to
nearly 100 sites around the country, said Americans "ought to
struggle constantly to identify what unites us -- that's more
important than what's different about us."
</P>
<P>
He announced a proposal to create educational opportunity zones
to reward school districts in poor urban and rural areas, news
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The year-long race initiative Clinton launched in San Diego,
California, in June was under fire for little progress.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Akron Beacon Journal, Clinton promised
to fight the "chilling" problem of police mistreating minorities.
He also said he is disturbed by racial disparities in the use of
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
In June Clinton announced a goal of reducing tensions among
racial and ethnic groups. The presidential race advisory panel has
drawn criticism for a slow start and little exchange of differing
views.
</P>
<P>
The White House also introduced a new public service ad
campaign aimed at increasing the dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
