<HEADLINE> IDB Assists Poorest Municipalities in El Salvador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank (IDB) today announced the approval of a 34.06
million U.S. dollar loan to El Salvador to finance improvement in
economic and social infrastructure in its poorest municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to finance a broad range of projects,
especially potable water, sanitation, and electricity, three areas
that will account for roughly half of the investments.
</P>
<P>
Other areas of investment will include repairs of schools and
health centers, purchase of educational equipment, reforestation,
rural roads, youth recreation facilities, as well as village
halls, depending on the priorities of the communities involved.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of the program is some 37.85 million dollars. In
addition to the IDB loan, which is for a 30-year term, local
counterpart will contribute total 3.79 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
