<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Iraq to Cooperate with UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council today again urged Iraq to cooperate fully with UNSCOM, the
U.N. Special Commission in charge of dismantling Iraq's weapons
of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The Council made the appeal in its presidential statement
endorsing the recommendations of the latest UNSCOM report for full
and expeditious implementation of the relevant U.N. resolutions on
UNSCOM work.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council reiterates its demand that Iraq fulfil
all its obligations as set out in all the relevant resolutions,"
said the statement reached after the Council consultation today.
</P>
<P>
The Council stressed that the effectiveness and speed of UNSCOM
work is "determined by the degree to which the Government of Iraq
cooperates in disclosing the full extent and disposition of its
proscribed programs and in granting UNSCOM unimpeded access to all
sites, documents, records and individuals," it said.
</P>
<P>
The Council also acknowledges the conclusion of the UNSCOM
report that UNSCOM respects the legitimate national security,
sovereignty and dignity concerns of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Council acknowledges that as Iraq complies with its
obligations under the relevant resolutions, UNSCOM and the
International Atomic Energy Agency would make the transition of
their work from investigation to monitoring.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM composition and access to sensitive inspection sites
have been among controversial issues between Iraq and UNSCOM and
tension once intensified between Iraq and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iraq expelled all Americans in the inspection teams on November
13 and UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler ordered to withdraw all
UNSCOM teams afterwards.
</P>
<P>
As a result of diplomatic efforts, UNSCOM resumed its work on
November 22, but the controversy over the sensitive sites still
remains.
</P>
<P>
Butler is scheduled to visit Baghdad from December 14-15 to
talk with the Iraq Government on the remaining issues, whose
resolution may eventually lead to the lifting of U.N. sanctions on
Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
