<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank, IMF, U.S. Support South Korean Reform Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Soon following the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) reached an agreement with South
Korea on economic reform and rescue package, the leaders of the
the World Bank, IMF and the U.S. voiced their support for it.
</P>
<P>
"We strongly welcome the reform program announced by the Korean
Government," the World Bank President, James D. Wolfensohn, said
in a statement issued here today.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Government "has asked the World Bank to resume
lending to Korea in support of its economic reforms. I am pleased
to respond speedyly and substantively to this request for our
involvement," the World Bank chief said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank plans to prepare a program of structural
adjustment loans for a total of up to 10 billion U.S. dollars.
These resources will be utilized to support reforms in the
financial sector, corporate governance, and other areas key to the
resumption of economic growth and poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
The last loan to South Korea before it graduated from the World
Bank borrowing was approved in December 1994, for some 75 million
U.S. dollars. Over the years, the World Bank lent the Korea a
total of 8.6 billion dollars of ordinary funds for 114 projects
and a total of 120 million of concessional funds from the
International Development Association (IDA). Outstanding loans and
credits total 1.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Michel Camdessus, the IMF Managing Director who is on a visit
to Seoul, also issued a statement, expressing his welcome for the
conclusion of talks with Korea on IMF package.
</P>
<P>
"The program comprises strengthened fiscal and monetary
policies, far-reaching financial sector reforms, and further
liberalization of trade and capital flows, as well as improvements
in the structure and governance of Korean corporation," Camdessus
said.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the package, the IMF will provide a
three-year stand-by credit up to some 21 billion dollar.
</P>
<P>
The IMF chief also revealed that some countries such as
Australia, Canada, France, Germany, Japan, Britain and the United
State are prepared to back Korea's program with the IMF. This
second line of defense is expected to be in excess of 20 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Secretary of Treasury Robert E. Rubin also
welcomed the IMF program for South Korea.
</P>
<P>
"The United States, along with a number of other countries from
around the world, is prepared to provide additional, contingent
financing to reinforce the Korean program," Rubin noted. "This
support could be made available for a temporary period, if
necessary, to supplement the resources made available by the
International Financial Institutions and those raised on the
private markets.It would be conditioned on the implementation of
the appropriate macroeconomic and structural policies supported by
the IMF, the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank."
</P>
<P>
Rubin said, his country is prepared to provide up to 5 billion
dollars in assistance from the Treasury's Exchange Stabilization
Fund for the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
