<HEADLINE> Turkey Explains Military Operation In Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel today defended his troops' incursion into northern Iraq,
saying Turkey has no intention to damage Iraq's interests.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here today, Demirel said Turkish
military operations inside Iraq aimed at cracking down "terrorist
elements" - the separatist Kurdish Workers' Party, or PKK.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to be explained that Turkey is determined not
to give the terrorist elements any chance to take the area as
their base to commit crimes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's repeated troop incursions into northern Iraq to ferret
out fugitive PKK guerrillas and its closer military cooperation
with Israel have been strongly criticized by Arab neighbors and
regarded as a threat to regional security.
</P>
<P>
Demirel, who is on a two day visit to the United Arab Emirates,
said "we have no problem and dispute with Iraq." He denied reports
that Turkey has rescinded a decision to set up a security zone in
the mountainous northern Iraq, saying Turkey "has never talked
about an area with such a name."
</P>
<P>
Demirel arrived here early Wednesday after a three-day visit to
Oman. His trip is aimed to explain Ankara's stand towards its
military actions into northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, Demirel accused Syria of harboring PKK members, which
he said was "not only a charge, but also a fact." He said the PKK
head is now in Damascus and orders militants to enter Turkey for
sabotage.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Turkey will allow U.S. warplanes to take off from its
air base to strike Baghdad, Demirel said he believed "there is not
any move aiming at the use of force against Iraq."
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq should completely implement the U.N. resolutions
to eliminate weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
Demirel is to return to Ankara Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
