<HEADLINE> President: Disabled Lead Normal Life in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel said today that the handicapped people in Turkey lead a
normal social life with self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
In his message to celebrate the World Disabled Day, Demirel
said the disabled in Turkey are not "different" from the other
citizens. The president is on a visit to the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
The disabled account for more than 10 percent of Turkey's
population, according to Demirel, who called it as one of the
thorniest social problems of the country.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's population stood at 61.1 million in 1994. According to
the World Health Organization, Turkey has 7.5 million disabled
people.
</P>
<P>
"It is one of our main duties to take care of our disabled
people and to solve their problems," Demirel said.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has set up a council for the disabled, which will meet
every three months to discuss and try to solve their employment
problems, Turkish State Minister Hasan Gemici told a symposium on
social security and employment of the disabled here today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
