<HEADLINE> Clinton Concerned about Police Mistreatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has promised to battle the "chilling" problem of police
mistreating minorities, and said he is disturbed by racial
disparities in the use of the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
In a newspaper interview to accompany his daylong forum on race
relations in Akron, Ohio, Clinton said unequal treatment by police
"eats at some communities in America as much as anything...even
though we've made a lot of progress."
</P>
<P>
Clinton also said in the Oval Office interview, published
Wednesday in the Akron Beacon Journal, that he is disturbed that
the death penalty is applied more frequently when a murder victim
is white, United Press International reported.
</P>
<P>
Clinton recalled during the interview Monday that virtually
every black journalist during a meeting with him earlier in the
year told him they had been stopped by a police officer "for no
apparent reason."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said that meeting and subsequent discussions with other
blacks and Hispanics reported similar experiences, according to
the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The president said he wanted to find a "highly visible public
forum" to air the issue of police discrimination, and suggested a
partial solution be found in the increased use of community-based
policing.
</P>
<P>
The president said, "What you want to do is to create an attitude
on the part of the law-enforcement officer that they don't stop
people just because they're black or brown or whatever."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
