<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Athens Can Meet EU Convergency Criteria in 1998, Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Greece could meet the
convergency criteria for European Economic and Monetary Union
(EMU) in 1998, National Economy and Finance Minister Yannos
Papantoniou said today.
</P>
<P>
Papantoniou told a Greek parliamentary committee that although
1998 would be a year of acceleration and structural changes, the
Greek government would win this battle.
</P>
<P>
Greece had changed the status of its economy and emerged from
instability, he said, but added that investments in both private
and public sectors needed a higher rate of growth and structural
changes were slow-moving.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government's budget for 1998, which aims at meeting
convergency criteria for EMU, was tabled last month to the
parliament for a final vote which is to take place on December 21.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry said in a statement today that the
European Union (EU) had endorsed changes proposed by Greece to its
economic alignment plan with the organization's other partners.
</P>
<P>
Under the changes, Greece's average consumer price inflation is
targeted at 5.6 percent in 1997, 3.7 percent in 1998 and 2.5
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The growth of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) is set at 3.5
percent in 1997, 3.7 percent in 1998 and 4.1 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The general government budget deficit is targeted at 4.2
percent of GDP in 1997, 2.4 percent in 1998 and 2.1 percent in
1999.
</P>
<P>
Greece is aiming to join EMU by January 1, 2001. Analysts here
believe that significant progress has for the past three years
been made with the fall in inflation and the budget deficit, but
the country still has a long and tough way to go. 
</P>
</TEXT>
