<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-03 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Returns Home, Ends Row With Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
returned home this evening, winding up his reconciliatory summit
with Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad bin Khalifa al-Thani in Riyadh.
</P>
<P>
Mediated by Saudi King Fahd, the president held talks with the
emir to end their deepening grudges that have marred relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued in Riyadh said the
tripartite meeting has led to "restoration of relations between
the two sisterly countries Egypt and Qatar to what they had been
before."
</P>
<P>
Mubarak told the press on his way back that he had spoken very
frankly on all topics of mutual concern with the Qatari emir.
</P>
<P>
He said he told the emir that differences between any two sides
are likely but "name-calling and insults by a minister against a
head of state and a whole people" are improper and unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to an allegation made by Qatari foreign
minister last month that Cairo was behind a failed coup in 1996 to
oust the emir, who himself toppled his father in a bloodless
palace coup in 1995. Egypt denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
"An atmosphere of frankness pervaded the meeting, which
occasioned an open discussion addressing grievances that caused
tension in Qatari-Egyptian relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
But there are still left-overs pertaining the Qatari minister's
remarks, which are "being discussed and on their way to be
solved," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said his lightning visit to Riyadh came in response to
King Fahd's invitation meet with the emir after the latter
expressed regret over what had happened between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has been on good terms with both Egypt and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian-Qatari ties deteriorated in October as Egypt boycotted
the fourth Middle East and North Africa Economic Conference in
Doha for lack of progress in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
Qatar responded with a ban on the entry of nationals of Egypt
and other nine countries as a security precaution for the Doha
meeting, infuriating Cairo and other Arab neighbors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971204.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ireland Welcomes Britain Repatriating IRA Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 3 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government has
welcomed Britain's action to repatriate three Irish Republican
Army (IRA) prisoners to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today the three IRA guerillas have been flown by a
British helicopter to a jail in the Irish town of Portlaoise,
according to press reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
Irish Justice minister John O'Donoghue was quoted as saying
today that the Dublin government welcomed the British move "in the
context of ongoing developments in the (Northern Ireland) peace
process".
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the British government is likely to
repatriate more IRA prisoners to Ireland in an effort to give an
impetus to the Northern Ireland peace process.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political arm of the IRA, has reportedly
demanded that any deal emerging from Northern Ireland provide for
the release of hundreds of jailed IRA guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
